t System - Security System Extension successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit Security System Extension\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> Security System Extension - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSecurity System Extension records events related to extension code being loaded by the security subsystem.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93115","SV-103203","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"9901","uuid":"dee2f4f7-2c52-438a-afd2-93ad05f02996","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205783","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205783","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205783","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205783r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205783","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000380","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit System Integrity\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> System Integrity - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSystem Integrity records events related to violations of integrity to the security subsystem.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93117","SV-103205","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"7139","uuid":"2685b9ab-c6ec-4bbf-8524-a84069aa252c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0AE6F9608FD7AFCB0C5C460ED34B32273218B477\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity successes.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205784","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205784","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205784","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205784r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205784","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000390","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit System Integrity\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> System Integrity - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSystem Integrity records events related to violations of integrity to the security subsystem.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93119","SV-103207","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"2740","uuid":"6b8a06e9-67d4-4c00-ab20-c1cbc6daed8a","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C01E85551F2CE477950BB8CA136B64B0A677DE22\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity failures.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205785","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205785","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205785","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205785r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205785","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000170","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Group Policy objects must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for Group Policy objects to include the following:\n\nThis can be done at the Policy level in Active Directory to apply to all group policies.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nSelect \"Advanced Features\" from the \"View\" Menu.\n\nNavigate to [Domain] >> System >> Policies in the left panel.\n\nRight click \"Policies\", select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button.\n\nSelect the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects or Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nThe three Success types listed below are defaults inherited from the Parent Object. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special (Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions; Properties: all \"Write\" type selected)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - blank (Permissions: none selected; Properties: one instance - Write gPLink, one instance - Write gPOptions)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant Organization Unit Objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for all Group Policy objects.\n\nOpen \"Group Policy Management\" (available from various menus or run \"gpmc.msc\").\n\nNavigate to \"Group Policy Objects\" in the domain being reviewed (Forest >> Domains >> Domain).\n\nFor each Group Policy object:\n\nSelect the Group Policy object item in the left pane.\n\nSelect the \"Delegation\" tab in the right pane.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button again and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings for any Group Policy object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects or Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nThe three Success types listed below are defaults inherited from the Parent Object. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special (Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions; Properties: all \"Write\" type selected)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - blank (Permissions: none selected; Properties: one instance - Write gPLink, one instance - Write gPOptions)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant Organization Unit Objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes Group Policy objects. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93121","SV-103209","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"4161","uuid":"c09a8149-5ded-4ada-9f09-00eb2d04b655","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC0D7072313CF01FF2EE2110038437718D006F3A\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Group Policy objects must be configured with proper audit settings.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205786","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205786","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205786","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205786r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205786","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000180","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the domain name and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for Domain object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - Special\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Domain Users\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Administrators\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner.)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the Domain object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the domain name and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Domain object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - Special\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Domain Users\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Administrators\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the Domain object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103211","V-93123","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"8744","uuid":"1b190dc7-a33b-440c-a026-bd0b77bb5377","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CDC3942881ADC11BC9E0E1612B17EB29FC7F6DC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205787","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205787","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205787","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205787r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205787","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000190","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Infrastructure object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Infrastructure\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for Infrastructure object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, All extended rights, Change infrastructure master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for Infrastructure object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Infrastructure\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Infrastructure object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, All extended rights, Change infrastructure master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the Infrastructure object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103213","V-93125","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"2251","uuid":"64bc904e-3965-4015-b336-0642be6f1467","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 67638AD463A87AB87F63067FE7BA5A0F03E32983\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Infrastructure object must be configured with proper audit settings.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205788","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205788","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205788","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205788r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205788","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000200","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain Controllers Organizational Unit (OU) object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the \"Domain Controllers OU\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Domain Controllers OU\" object and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for Domain Controllers OU object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: all create, delete and modify permissions)\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Write all properties\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the Domain Controller OU object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the \"Domain Controllers OU\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Domain Controllers OU\" object and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Domain Controllers OU object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: all create, delete and modify permissions)\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Write all properties\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the Domain Controller OU object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103215","V-93127","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"7111","uuid":"f8174042-0a0e-4703-8558-eb2d686d483c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F0C6AAF5FA6A30739459FFB24C19EB9715627580\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain Controllers Organizational Unit (OU) object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205789","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205789","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205789","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205789r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205789","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000210","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory AdminSDHolder object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"AdminSDHolder\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for AdminSDHolder object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the \"AdminSDHolder\" object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"AdminSDHolder\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the \"AdminSDHolder\" object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the AdminSDHolder object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103217","V-93129","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"1644","uuid":"5f0a9273-f6cb-41ea-a78e-d2a091efe4b7","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 86DB0AD450486BA90AE0F1BF91BFA9EB23E5B1B9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory AdminSDHolder object must be configured with proper audit settings.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205790","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205790","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205790","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205790r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205790","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory RID Manager$ object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"RID Manager$\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for RID Manager$ object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n (Access - Special = Write all properties, All extended rights, Change RID master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the \"RID Manager$\" object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"RID Manager$\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the \"RID Manager$\" object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n (Access - Special = Write all properties, All extended rights, Change RID master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the RID Manager$ object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93131","SV-103219","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"6351","uuid":"2979612f-496d-4694-a6bc-5ca6b59572c3","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F8836D0CB98F5A36A7E5D698C2E184BE470AC0FC\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory RID Manager$ object must be configured with proper audit settings.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205791","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205791","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205791","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205791r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205791","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000240","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> DS Access >> \"Directory Service Access\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nSecurity Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDS Access >> Directory Service Access - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Directory Service Access records events related to users accessing an Active Directory object.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103221","V-93133","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"2929","uuid":"f6841056-06ee-4859-be58-1f52c60f75a7","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205792","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205792","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205792","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205792r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205792","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000250","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> DS Access >> \"Directory Service Access\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nSecurity Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDS Access >> Directory Service Access - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Directory Service Access records events related to users accessing an Active Directory object.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103223","V-93135","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"8837","uuid":"d7436710-3265-41bc-b67b-3030d09388d8","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D87B2D87B754DF9B7C09EE01F82BC2AA0A7FBF54\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access failures.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205793","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205793","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205793","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205793r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205793","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000260","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Changes successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> DS Access >> \"Directory Service Changes\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nSecurity Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDS Access >> Directory Service Changes - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Directory Service Changes records events related to changes made to objects in Active Directory Domain Services.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93137","SV-103225","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"7239","uuid":"12ab158e-8223-4a68-ad2b-f1e6429e5a7d","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D3E3493A371D05124DA9980D4AC03BD4AE23ABBE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Changes successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205795","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205795","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205795","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-205795r958736_rule","rule_id":"SV-205795","rule_version":"WN19-AC-000010","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 account lockout duration must be configured to 15 minutes or greater.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Account Policies >> Account Lockout Policy >> \"Account lockout duration\" to \"15\" minutes or greater.\n\nA value of \"0\" is also acceptable, requiring an administrator to unlock the account.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Account Policies >> Account Lockout Policy.\n\nIf the \"Account lockout duration\" is less than \"15\" minutes (excluding \"0\"), this is a finding.\n\nFor server core installations, run the following command:\n\nSecedit /Export /Areas SecurityPolicy /CFG C:\\Path\\FileName.Txt\n\nIf \"LockoutDuration\" is less than \"15\" (excluding \"0\") in the file, this is a finding.\n\nConfiguring this to \"0\", requiring an administrator to unlock the account, is more restrictive and is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The account lockout feature, when enabled, prevents brute-force password attacks on the system. This parameter specifies the period of time that an account will remain locked after the specified number of failed logon attempts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93145","SV-103233","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"4001","uuid":"48bdfc2f-aa95-4376-ab3e-78a782c66a69","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 53918B7C4A48DF2D407A8AAB7D70490B7ACEA3C1\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 account lockout duration must be configured to 15 minutes or greater.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205796","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205796","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205796","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-205796r958752_rule","rule_id":"SV-205796","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000270","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Application event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Event Log Service >> Application >> \"Specify the maximum log file size (KB)\" to \"Enabled\" with a \"Maximum Log Size (KB)\" of \"32768\" or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is configured to write events directly to an audit server, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\EventLog\\Application\\\n\nValue Name: MaxSize\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00008000 (32768) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inadequate log size will cause the log to fill up quickly. This may prevent audit events from being recorded properly and require frequent attention by administrative personnel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103265","V-93177","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"5470","uuid":"d6a67761-9e4c-402b-873d-ae08d68d726d","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 986682B978ED716BC0C6516D51C0F6D25F30C8CA\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Application event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205797","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205797","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205797","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-205797r1186384_rule","rule_id":"SV-205797","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000280","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 security event log size must be configured to a value that holds at least one week's worth of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Event Log Service >> Security >> \"Specify the maximum log file size (KB)\" to \"Enabled\" with a \"Maximum Log Size (KB)\" of a value that will contain one week of audit records or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is configured to write events directly to an audit server, this is not applicable.\n\nThe registry configuration setting below must be set (at least) to a value equal to the size needed to contain one week's worth of audit records in the security event log. The value used below is an example that assumes a typical week\u2019s log size of 5GB.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nNote: The following registry entry is an example; the value must equal at least one week's worth of records.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\EventLog\\Security\\\n\nValue Name: MaxSize\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue:0x49960800 (5120000) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inadequate log size will cause the log to fill up quickly. This may prevent audit events from being recorded properly and require frequent attention by administrative personnel. System administrators (SAs) must monitor the volume of security event audit records and increase the registry value for the log size as needed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103267","V-93179","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"4822","uuid":"9411a861-416b-41ee-a757-3b0a505dbf93","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E6395CEB9ED6C2DE5E76EAAFF4B30770244A7438\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 security event log size must be configured to a value that holds at least one week's worth of audit records.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205798","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205798","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205798","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-205798r958752_rule","rule_id":"SV-205798","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000290","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 System event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Event Log Service >> System >> \"Specify the maximum log file size (KB)\" to \"Enabled\" with a \"Maximum Log Size (KB)\" of \"32768\" or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is configured to write events directly to an audit server, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\EventLog\\System\\\n\nValue Name: MaxSize\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00008000 (32768) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inadequate log size will cause the log to fill up quickly. This may prevent audit events from being recorded properly and require frequent attention by administrative personnel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103269","V-93181","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"6546","uuid":"31abd13e-5f67-498e-b567-af82f465a7ce","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 529F50CD163EC88361BC7F835CBA497AA3111B41\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 System event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205799","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205799","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205799","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-205799r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-205799","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000010","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 audit records must be backed up to a different system or media than the system being audited.","fix_text":"Establish and implement a process for backing up log data to another system or media other than the system being audited.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if a process to back up log data to a different system or media than the system being audited has been implemented.\n\nIf it has not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protection of log data includes assuring the log data is not accidentally lost or deleted. Audit information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93183","SV-103271","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5219","uuid":"541f170b-c112-4efb-b778-043ffb9c0206","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 301E51C435D847AF7FACE4F340609A77A80B48A6\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 audit records must be backed up to a different system or media than the system being audited.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205800","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205800","title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205800","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","rule_id_src":"SV-205800r1051077_rule","rule_id":"SV-205800","rule_version":"WN19-00-000440","rule_title":"The Windows Server 2019 time service must synchronize with an appropriate DOD time source.","fix_text":"Configure the system to synchronize time with an appropriate DOD time source.\n\nDomain-joined systems use NT5DS to synchronize time from other systems in the domain by default.\n\nIf the system needs to be configured to an NTP server, configure the system to point to an authorized time server by setting the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Windows Time Service >> Time Providers >> \"Configure Windows NTP Client\" to \"Enabled\", and configure the \"NtpServer\" field to point to an appropriate DOD time server.\n\nThe US Naval Observatory operates stratum 1 time servers, which are identified at:\nhttps://www.cnmoc.usff.navy.mil/Our-Commands/United-States-Naval-Observatory/Precise-Time-Department/Network-Time-Protocol-NTP/\n\nTime synchronization will occur through a hierarchy of time servers down to the local level. Clients and lower-level servers will synchronize with an authorized time server in the hierarchy.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the Windows time service configuration.\n\nOpen an elevated \"Command Prompt\" (run as administrator).\n\nEnter \"W32tm /query /configuration\".\n\nDomain-joined systems (excluding the domain controller with the PDC emulator role):\n\nIf the value for \"Type\" under \"NTP Client\" is not \"NT5DS\", this is a finding.\n\nOther systems:\n\nIf systems are configured with a \"Type\" of \"NTP\", including standalone or nondomain-joined systems and the domain controller with the PDC Emulator role, and do not have a DOD time server defined for \"NTPServer\", this is a finding.\n\nTo determine the domain controller with the PDC Emulator role:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"Get-ADDomain | FT PDCEmulator\".","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The Windows Time Service controls time synchronization settings. Time synchronization is essential for authentication and auditing purposes. If the Windows Time Service is used, it must synchronize with a secure, authorized time source. Domain-joined systems are automatically configured to synchronize with domain controllers. If an NTP server is configured, it must synchronize with a secure, authorized time source.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93187","SV-103275","CCI-004923","CCI-001891"],"reference_identifier":"1283","uuid":"0a544542-85a0-44ea-9ef7-97cf79f5b9cf","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3F1158584ED80E36069C98EF4EF810F90F8CAD08\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'The Windows Server 2019 time service must synchronize with an appropriate DOD time source.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205801","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205801","title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205801","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","rule_id_src":"SV-205801r1051078_rule","rule_id":"SV-205801","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000420","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must prevent users from changing installation options.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Installer >> \"Allow user control over installs\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\\n\nValue Name: EnableUserControl\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Installation options for applications are typically controlled by administrators. This setting prevents users from changing installation options that may bypass security features.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93199","SV-103287","CCI-003980","CCI-001812"],"reference_identifier":"5838","uuid":"c6896f6d-0851-40e4-8c46-d6477bdb4733","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205802","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205802","title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205802","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","rule_id_src":"SV-205802r1051079_rule","rule_id":"SV-205802","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000430","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must disable the Windows Installer Always install with elevated privileges option.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Installer >> \"Always install with elevated privileges\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\\n\nValue Name: AlwaysInstallElevated\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Standard user accounts must not be granted elevated privileges. Enabling Windows Installer to elevate privileges when installing applications can allow malicious persons and applications to gain full control of a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93201","SV-103289","CCI-003980","CCI-001812"],"reference_identifier":"4555","uuid":"0b6b6a4b-ebed-42d3-bf2e-2bddef216ff5","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8F7FCCAA737C1696C8DFAE16D9BC23150E643047\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must disable the Windows Installer Always install with elevated privileges option.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205803","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205803","title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205803","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","rule_id_src":"SV-205803r958794_rule","rule_id":"SV-205803","rule_version":"WN19-00-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 system files must be monitored for unauthorized changes.","fix_text":"Monitor the system for unauthorized changes to system files (e.g., *.exe, *.bat, *.com, *.cmd, and *.dll) against a baseline on a weekly basis. This can be done with the use of various monitoring tools.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine whether the system is monitored for unauthorized changes to system files (e.g., *.exe, *.bat, *.com, *.cmd, and *.dll) against a baseline on a weekly basis.\n\nIf system files are not monitored for unauthorized changes, this is a finding.\n\nAn approved and properly configured solution will contain both a list of baselines that includes all system file locations and a file comparison task that is scheduled to run at least weekly.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Monitoring system files for changes against a baseline on a regular basis may help detect the possible introduction of malicious code on a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103291","V-93203","CCI-001744"],"reference_identifier":"2390","uuid":"0e0c0053-9806-42bb-9e42-1db2906021ed","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E0544DAB5BAA2635626031CE3605D34013C112CC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 system files must be monitored for unauthorized changes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205804","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205804","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205804","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-205804r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-205804","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000210","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Autoplay must be turned off for non-volume devices.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> AutoPlay Policies >> \"Disallow Autoplay for non-volume devices\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoAutoplayfornonVolume\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing AutoPlay to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. AutoPlay begins reading from a drive as soon as media is inserted into the drive. As a result, the setup file of programs or music on audio media may start. This setting will disable AutoPlay for non-volume devices, such as Media Transfer Protocol (MTP) devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93373","SV-103459","CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"6122","uuid":"ebbbb678-370c-4406-b64a-0207da9e7730","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205805","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205805","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205805","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-205805r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-205805","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 default AutoRun behavior must be configured to prevent AutoRun commands.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> AutoPlay Policies >> \"Set the default behavior for AutoRun\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Do not execute any autorun commands\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoAutorun\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing AutoRun commands to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. Configuring this setting prevents AutoRun commands from executing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93375","SV-103461","CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"2840","uuid":"ba6e57fd-f7aa-4e2c-abd5-134496f403e7","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205806","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205806","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205806","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-205806r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-205806","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000230","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 AutoPlay must be disabled for all drives.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> AutoPlay Policies >> \"Turn off AutoPlay\" to \"Enabled\" with \"All Drives\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\policies\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoDriveTypeAutoRun\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x000000ff (255)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing AutoPlay to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. AutoPlay begins reading from a drive as soon media is inserted into the drive. As a result, the setup file of programs or music on audio media may start. By default, AutoPlay is disabled on removable drives, such as the floppy disk drive (but not the CD-ROM drive) and on network drives. Enabling this policy disables AutoPlay on all drives.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93377","SV-103463","CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"5534","uuid":"f3ccdfa7-b3b2-495c-8828-0ede1f87e359","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6AF19F2B1AB133C2949D4FDEE4B25EDB398180DE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 AutoPlay must be disabled for all drives.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205807","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205807","title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205807","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","rule_id_src":"SV-205807r958808_rule","rule_id":"SV-205807","rule_version":"WN19-00-000080","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.","fix_text":"Configure an application allowlisting program to employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.\n\nConfiguration of allowlisting applications will vary by the program. AppLocker is an allowlisting application built into Windows Server.\n\nIf AppLocker is used, it is configured through group policy in Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Application Control Policies >> AppLocker.\n\nImplementation guidance for AppLocker is available at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-defender-application-control/applocker/applocker-policies-deployment-guide","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system employs a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.\n\nIf an application allowlisting program is not in use on the system, this is a finding.\n\nConfiguration of allowlisting applications will vary by the program.\n\nAppLocker is an allowlisting application built into Windows Server. A deny-by-default implementation is initiated by enabling any AppLocker rules within a category, only allowing what is specified by defined rules.\n\nIf AppLocker is used, perform the following to view the configuration of AppLocker:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nIf the AppLocker PowerShell module has not been imported previously, execute the following first:\n\nImport-Module AppLocker\n\nExecute the following command, substituting [c:\\temp\\file.xml] with a location and file name appropriate for the system:\n\nGet-AppLockerPolicy -Effective -XML > c:\\temp\\file.xml\n\nThis will produce an xml file with the effective settings that can be viewed in a browser or opened in a program such as Excel for review.\n\nImplementation guidance for AppLocker is available at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-defender-application-control/applocker/applocker-policies-deployment-guide","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using an allowlist provides a configuration management method to allow the execution of only authorized software. Using only authorized software decreases risk by limiting the number of potential vulnerabilities.\n\nThe organization must identify authorized software programs and only permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as allowlisting.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93379","SV-103465","CCI-001774"],"reference_identifier":"7941","uuid":"b5224537-120d-4e9d-a917-3ae4efb5f894","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6502B5D17AA9B9CCB020D4F743CE8E747B448C6E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205808","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205808","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205808","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205808r1051080_rule","rule_id":"SV-205808","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000340","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must not save passwords in the Remote Desktop Client.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Remote Desktop Services >> Remote Desktop Connection Client >> \"Do not allow passwords to be saved\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Terminal Services\\\n\nValue Name: DisablePasswordSaving\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Saving passwords in the Remote Desktop Client could allow an unauthorized user to establish a remote desktop session to another system. The system must be configured to prevent users from saving passwords in the Remote Desktop Client.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93425","SV-103511","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"9234","uuid":"e94cbea5-33e6-4df3-8640-babad8d07cf2","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AA066F2F2573DB3C0D9C3F8C0E6832DBFF4F6D88\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must not save passwords in the Remote Desktop Client.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205809","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205809","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205809","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205809r1051081_rule","rule_id":"SV-205809","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000360","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Remote Desktop Services must always prompt a client for passwords upon connection.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Remote Desktop Services >> Remote Desktop Session Host >> Security >> \"Always prompt for password upon connection\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Terminal Services\\\n\nValue Name: fPromptForPassword\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This setting controls the ability of users to supply passwords automatically as part of their remote desktop connection. Disabling this setting would allow anyone to use the stored credentials in a connection item to connect to the terminal server.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93427","SV-103513","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"8845","uuid":"2d07e46e-d536-4b1f-8a10-8025e7a74193","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C60663FE45F09EE9E076AA19C9BBD233B9CC11B7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Remote Desktop Services must always prompt a client for passwords upon connection.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205810","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205810","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205810","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205810r1051082_rule","rule_id":"SV-205810","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000520","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not store RunAs credentials.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) >> WinRM Service >> \"Disallow WinRM from storing RunAs credentials\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WinRM\\Service\\\n\nValue Name: DisableRunAs\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Storage of administrative credentials could allow unauthorized access. Disallowing the storage of RunAs credentials for Windows Remote Management will prevent them from being used with plug-ins.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103515","V-93429","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"6549","uuid":"efd298d7-4901-433b-b061-c27418e1965d","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2FD4FD5ACD7FC7C8EF498352BFF03784F09125FC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not store RunAs credentials.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205811","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205811","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205811","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205811r1051083_rule","rule_id":"SV-205811","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000380","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 User Account Control approval mode for the built-in Administrator must be enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"User Account Control: Admin Approval Mode for the Built-in Administrator account\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"UAC requirements are NA for Server Core installations (this is the default installation option for Windows Server 2019 versus Server with Desktop Experience).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: FilterAdministratorToken\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"User Account Control (UAC) is a security mechanism for limiting the elevation of privileges, including administrative accounts, unless authorized. This setting configures the built-in Administrator account so that it runs in Admin Approval Mode.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103517","V-93431","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"9946","uuid":"a7e5d4f3-36ab-4be2-89a9-b87bbb7c2ce9","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C9BF5543EE23B725942E1ADA07B23FF715C8BC0A\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 User Account Control approval mode for the built-in Administrator must be enabled.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205812","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205812","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205812","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205812r1051084_rule","rule_id":"SV-205812","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000410","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must automatically deny standard user requests for elevation.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"User Account Control: Behavior of the elevation prompt for standard users\" to \"Automatically deny elevation requests\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"UAC requirements are NA for Server Core installations (this is the default installation option for Windows Server 2019 versus Server with Desktop Experience).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: ConsentPromptBehaviorUser\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"User Account Control (UAC) is a security mechanism for limiting the elevation of privileges, including administrative accounts, unless authorized. This setting controls the behavior of elevation when requested by a standard user account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93433","SV-103519","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"3644","uuid":"55f6986f-4265-4050-a1b3-09739a819d66","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3E251E9483A85D6C36BB50DC6D428C736E40108D\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must automatically deny standard user requests for elevation.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205813","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205813","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205813","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205813r1051085_rule","rule_id":"SV-205813","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000440","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode, enabling UAC.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"User Account Control: Run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"UAC requirements are NA for Server Core installations (this is the default installation option for Windows Server 2019 versus Server with Desktop Experience).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: EnableLUA\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"User Account Control (UAC) is a security mechanism for limiting the elevation of privileges, including administrative accounts, unless authorized. This setting enables UAC.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93435","SV-103521","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"4088","uuid":"bd77d3b2-1b4c-4e2e-9e1a-7e70c51848f9","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 56C9A3E6C2AD014CAF88760116F506F03FB0579F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode, enabling UAC.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205814","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205814","title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205814","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","rule_id_src":"SV-205814r971545_rule","rule_id":"SV-205814","rule_version":"WN19-MS-000040","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must restrict unauthenticated Remote Procedure Call (RPC) clients from connecting to the RPC server on domain-joined member servers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Remote Procedure Call >> \"Restrict Unauthenticated RPC clients\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Authenticated\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to member servers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems. It is NA for domain controllers.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Rpc\\\n\nValue Name:  RestrictRemoteClients\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthenticated RPC clients may allow anonymous access to sensitive information. Configuring RPC to restrict unauthenticated RPC clients from connecting to the RPC server will prevent anonymous connections.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93453","SV-103539","CCI-001967"],"reference_identifier":"8487","uuid":"8d9a987e-1b6b-46f6-920c-94300f77ab5b","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205815","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205815","title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205815","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","rule_id_src":"SV-205815r971545_rule","rule_id":"SV-205815","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000090","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 computer account password must not be prevented from being reset.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Disable machine account password changes\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: DisablePasswordChange\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Computer account passwords are changed automatically on a regular basis. Disabling automatic password changes can make the system more vulnerable to malicious access. Frequent password changes can be a significant safeguard for the system. A new password for the computer account will be generated every 30 days.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93455","SV-103541","CCI-001967"],"reference_identifier":"8424","uuid":"bca3f359-8d27-4053-94f2-7f2ea410864c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 791B0160B4984EFB2AEEECA22093153F2810F7CD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 computer account password must not be prevented from being reset.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205816","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205816","title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205816","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","rule_id_src":"SV-205816r958848_rule","rule_id":"SV-205816","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000480","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) client must not allow unencrypted traffic.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) >> WinRM Client >> \"Allow unencrypted traffic\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WinRM\\Client\\\n\nValue Name: AllowUnencryptedTraffic\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unencrypted remote access to a system can allow sensitive information to be compromised. Windows remote management connections must be encrypted to prevent this.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103585","V-93499","CCI-002890","CCI-003123"],"reference_identifier":"9764","uuid":"2d512893-d230-41fc-82cb-940c2064d0d4","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205817","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205817","title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205817","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","rule_id_src":"SV-205817r958848_rule","rule_id":"SV-205817","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000510","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not allow unencrypted traffic.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) >> WinRM Service >> \"Allow unencrypted traffic\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WinRM\\Service\\\n\nValue Name: AllowUnencryptedTraffic\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unencrypted remote access to a system can allow sensitive information to be compromised. Windows remote management connections must be encrypted to prevent this.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103587","V-93501","CCI-002890","CCI-003123"],"reference_identifier":"4361","uuid":"f587f3a9-131f-4b12-8550-757fc89a663a","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 93D46B4492178C226E5FFCCC21703B442279D717\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not allow unencrypted traffic.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205818","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205818","title":"SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205818","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176","rule_id_src":"SV-205818r987791_rule","rule_id":"SV-205818","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000140","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must use separate, NSA-approved (Type 1) cryptography to protect the directory data in transit for directory service implementations at a classified confidentiality level when replication data traverses a network cleared to a lower level than the data.","fix_text":"Configure NSA-approved (Type 1) cryptography to protect the directory data in transit for directory service implementations at a classified confidentiality level that transfer replication data through a network cleared to a lower level than the data.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the organization network diagram(s) or documentation to determine the level of classification for the network(s) over which replication data is transmitted.\n\nDetermine the classification level of the Windows domain controller.\n\nIf the classification level of the Windows domain controller is higher than the level of the networks, review the organization network diagram(s) and directory implementation documentation to determine if NSA-approved encryption is used to protect the replication network traffic.\n\nIf the classification level of the Windows domain controller is higher than the level of the network traversed and NSA-approved encryption is not used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Directory data that is not appropriately encrypted is subject to compromise. Commercial-grade encryption does not provide adequate protection when the classification level of directory data in transit is higher than the level of the network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93513","SV-103599","CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"5270","uuid":"0c6a066c-eacb-47b5-ab19-0ef78158ae0f","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 71B2500A7E42EED1BC89459C41E7DED965879CB6\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must use separate, NSA-approved (Type 1) cryptography to protect the directory data in transit for directory service implementations at a classified confidentiality level when replication data traverses a network cleared to a lower level than the data.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205819","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205819","title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205819","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","rule_id_src":"SV-205819r958902_rule","rule_id":"SV-205819","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000060","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to ignore NetBIOS name release requests except from WINS servers.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MSS (Legacy) >> \"MSS: (NoNameReleaseOnDemand) Allow the computer to ignore NetBIOS name release requests except from WINS servers\" to \"Enabled\".\n\nThis policy setting requires the installation of the MSS-Legacy custom templates included with the STIG package. \"MSS-Legacy.admx\" and \"MSS-Legacy.adml\" must be copied to the \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions and \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions\\en-US directories respectively.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netbt\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name:  NoNameReleaseOnDemand\n\nValue Type:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the system to ignore name release requests, except from WINS servers, prevents a denial of service (DoS) attack. The DoS consists of sending a NetBIOS name release request to the server for each entry in the server's cache, causing a response delay in the normal operation of the server's WINS resolution capability.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103627","V-93541","CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"3126","uuid":"36f3cff9-8eb8-48b5-b37d-97856c034017","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FDAC8674052EEF4BE5E11857AA89CC616AF1798A\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to ignore NetBIOS name release requests except from WINS servers.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205820","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205820","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205820","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205820r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205820","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000320","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 domain controllers must require LDAP access signing.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain controller: LDAP server signing requirements\" to \"Require signing\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NTDS\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: LDAPServerIntegrity\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000002 (2)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unsigned network traffic is susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks, where an intruder captures packets between the server and the client and modifies them before forwarding them to the client. In the case of an LDAP server, this means that an attacker could cause a client to make decisions based on false records from the LDAP directory. The risk of an attacker pulling this off can be decreased by implementing strong physical security measures to protect the network infrastructure. Furthermore, implementing Internet Protocol security (IPsec) authentication header mode (AH), which performs mutual authentication and packet integrity for Internet Protocol (IP) traffic, can make all types of man-in-the-middle attacks extremely difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93545","SV-103631","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"9143","uuid":"42e25789-b90b-4045-a858-a0fa53a079c7","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205821","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205821","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205821","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205821r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205821","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000060","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Domain member: Digitally encrypt or sign secure channel data (always) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Digitally encrypt or sign secure channel data (always)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: RequireSignOrSeal\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Requests sent on the secure channel are authenticated, and sensitive information (such as passwords) is encrypted, but not all information is encrypted. If this policy is enabled, outgoing secure channel traffic will be encrypted and signed.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93547","SV-103633","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"6814","uuid":"100af52b-54d9-4ec1-9eb1-b2d255356a09","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205822","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205822","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205822","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205822r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205822","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000070","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Domain member: Digitally encrypt secure channel data (when possible) must be configured to enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Digitally encrypt secure channel data (when possible)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: SealSecureChannel\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Requests sent on the secure channel are authenticated, and sensitive information (such as passwords) is encrypted, but not all information is encrypted. If this policy is enabled, outgoing secure channel traffic will be encrypted.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93549","SV-103635","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"9655","uuid":"e19c36ca-2a83-4f0e-8d19-202c08a912ff","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205823","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205823","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205823","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205823r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205823","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000080","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Domain member: Digitally sign secure channel data (when possible) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Digitally sign secure channel data (when possible)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: SignSecureChannel\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Requests sent on the secure channel are authenticated, and sensitive information (such as passwords) is encrypted, but the channel is not integrity checked. If this policy is enabled, outgoing secure channel traffic will be signed.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93551","SV-103637","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"9798","uuid":"cb63c577-7d4d-45ec-81e6-75b2f1912979","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 23519A0678FE90212EBB4AD12F71E6E57092DC93\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 setting Domain member: Digitally sign secure channel data (when possible) must be configured to Enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205824","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205824","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205824","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205824r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205824","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000110","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to require a strong session key.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Require strong (Windows 2000 or Later) session key\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: RequireStrongKey\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)\n \nThis setting may prevent a system from being joined to a domain if not configured consistently between systems.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A computer connecting to a domain controller will establish a secure channel. The secure channel connection may be subject to compromise, such as hijacking or eavesdropping, if strong session keys are not used to establish the connection. Requiring strong session keys enforces 128-bit encryption between systems.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103639","V-93553","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"6545","uuid":"721b3180-a732-493c-971e-a762daa6ddfe","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7A18FC4208AA03B43F042BDEE6C2AFF8B4C33B2F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to require a strong session key.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205825","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205825","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205825","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205825r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205825","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000160","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network client: Digitally sign communications (always) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Microsoft network client: Digitally sign communications (always)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\LanmanWorkstation\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: RequireSecuritySignature\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The server message block (SMB) protocol provides the basis for many network operations. Digitally signed SMB packets aid in preventing man-in-the-middle attacks. If this policy is enabled, the SMB client will only communicate with an SMB server that performs SMB packet signing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93555","SV-103641","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"1716","uuid":"e4cca39d-df44-4da5-9ad5-a53e6462d32d","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F8CAB3C2F087F3915B209C4DECD3A431F005C62D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network client: Digitally sign communications (always) must be configured to Enabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205826","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205826","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205826","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205826r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205826","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000170","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network client: Digitally sign communications (if server agrees) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Microsoft network client: Digitally sign communications (if server agrees)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\LanmanWorkstation\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: EnableSecuritySignature\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The server message block (SMB) protocol provides the basis for many network operations. If this policy is enabled, the SMB client will request packet signing when communicating with an SMB server that is enabled or required to perform SMB packet signing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93557","SV-103643","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"4402","uuid":"73135a31-b1c8-4511-9084-9a48140aee96","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D88E53DBF1022A3BFCCA28BFB241B165BF4785F5\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network client: Digitally sign communications (if server agrees) must be configured to Enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205827","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205827","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205827","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205827r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205827","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000190","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (always) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (always)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\LanManServer\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: RequireSecuritySignature\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The server message block (SMB) protocol provides the basis for many network operations. Digitally signed SMB packets aid in preventing man-in-the-middle attacks. If this policy is enabled, the SMB server will only communicate with an SMB client that performs SMB packet signing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103645","V-93559","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"6891","uuid":"d9709ebe-4389-4571-aa20-28e60babdabd","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7571C7925FB4196480BB5CDFFBF2C6F8F23D0181\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (always) must be configured to Enabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205828","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205828","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205828","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205828r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205828","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000200","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (if client agrees) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (if client agrees)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\LanManServer\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: EnableSecuritySignature\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The server message block (SMB) protocol provides the basis for many network operations. Digitally signed SMB packets aid in preventing man-in-the-middle attacks. If this policy is enabled, the SMB server will negotiate SMB packet signing as requested by the client.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93561","SV-103647","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"5570","uuid":"494fc623-40d0-4933-bf35-39af3773e6b1","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205829","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205829","title":"SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205829","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189","rule_id_src":"SV-205829r958912_rule","rule_id":"SV-205829","rule_version":"WN19-00-000260","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must implement protection methods such as TLS, encrypted VPNs, or IPsec if the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process.","fix_text":"Configure protection methods such as TLS, encrypted VPNs, or IPsec when the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process, verify protection methods such as TLS, encrypted VPNs, or IPsec have been implemented.\n\nIf protection methods have not been implemented, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information can be either unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during preparation for transmission, for example, during aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during packing/unpacking. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information.\n\nEnsuring the confidentiality of transmitted information requires the operating system to take measures in preparing information for transmission. This can be accomplished via access control and encryption.\n\nUse of this requirement will be limited to situations where the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process. When transmitting data, operating systems need to support transmission protection mechanisms such as TLS, encrypted VPNs, or IPsec.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189, SRG-OS-000426-GPOS-00190","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103629","V-93543","CCI-002420","CCI-002422"],"reference_identifier":"1819","uuid":"f78d6ea9-d772-493d-b385-77aab7208631","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7BC3EB93BFEFA0E01634E5AD619FAF970EC3A9A0\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must implement protection methods such as TLS, encrypted VPNs, or IPsec if the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205830","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205830","title":"SRG-OS-000433-GPOS-00192","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205830","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000433-GPOS-00192","rule_id_src":"SV-205830r958928_rule","rule_id":"SV-205830","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000310","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Explorer Data Execution Prevention must be enabled.","fix_text":"The default behavior is for data execution prevention to be turned on for File Explorer.\n\nIf this needs to be corrected, configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> File Explorer >> \"Turn off Data Execution Prevention for Explorer\" to \"Not Configured\" or \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The default behavior is for Data Execution Prevention to be turned on for File Explorer.\n\nIf the registry value name below does not exist, this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"0\", this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"1\", this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoDataExecutionPrevention\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0) (or if the Value Name does not exist)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Data Execution Prevention provides additional protection by performing checks on memory to help prevent malicious code from running. This setting will prevent Data Execution Prevention from being turned off for File Explorer.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103649","V-93563","CCI-002824"],"reference_identifier":"8383","uuid":"f469943a-b12a-4338-8c8b-3e85f9cf0970","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B7011091CBDAF2FB1C24C263CC01A0F67AECA021\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Explorer Data Execution Prevention must be enabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205832","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205832","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205832","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-205832r991578_rule","rule_id":"SV-205832","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000070","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Account Logon - Credential Validation successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Account Logon >> \"Audit Credential Validation\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nAccount Logon >> Credential Validation - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nCredential Validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103241","V-93153","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"7872","uuid":"105a047c-e63e-41b1-84f1-497b9a9b29f4","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 77BFCD9EAF8052AB917636FF75CE469B9D897A40\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Account Logon - Credential Validation successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205833","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205833","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205833","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-205833r991578_rule","rule_id":"SV-205833","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000080","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Account Logon - Credential Validation failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Account Logon >> \"Audit Credential Validation\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nAccount Logon >> Credential Validation - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nCredential Validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103243","V-93155","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8701","uuid":"096c8b4f-61a1-4a9f-9463-82609747fd2d","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D96CD632BF8A9396794B596F53E91318960A0552\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Account Logon - Credential Validation failures.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205834","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205834","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205834","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-205834r991578_rule","rule_id":"SV-205834","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000170","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Logon/Logoff - Group Membership successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Logon/Logoff >> \"Audit Group Membership\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nLogon/Logoff >> Group Membership - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Group Membership records information related to the group membership of a user's logon token.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93159","SV-103247","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"6636","uuid":"56fffe25-1abd-41b2-ace3-bc5e238adb94","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B991274A9A011B07654D3C1B778D9BAC34065F93\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Logon/Logoff - Group Membership successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205835","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205835","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205835","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-205835r991578_rule","rule_id":"SV-205835","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000210","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Logon/Logoff - Special Logon successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Logon/Logoff >> \"Audit Special Logon\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nLogon/Logoff >> Special Logon - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSpecial Logon records special logons that have administrative privileges and can be used to elevate processes.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000472-GPOS-00217, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218, SRG-OS-000475-GPOS-00220","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93161","SV-103249","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"9783","uuid":"355782ee-75a5-43d9-a506-28a2bcfbab3e","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C019138DB15C010D4338B1B9D1D2CA675565138B\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Logon/Logoff - Special Logon successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205836","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205836","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205836","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-205836r991578_rule","rule_id":"SV-205836","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Other Object Access Events\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nObject Access >> Other Object Access Events - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing for other object access records events related to the management of task scheduler jobs and COM+ objects.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103251","V-93163","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3644","uuid":"e06be0ae-22cd-4aee-bbde-7111277f3481","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 03201AD7629CE2AC864C17F66469A6A0A5D6C7E1\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205837","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205837","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205837","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-205837r991578_rule","rule_id":"SV-205837","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000230","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Other Object Access Events\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nObject Access >> Other Object Access Events - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing for other object access records events related to the management of task scheduler jobs and COM+ objects.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103253","V-93165","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3975","uuid":"6be9a323-6391-4a03-ab54-54a630ad347b","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D959009A085E2549CBFAE4B62CF8BBAEFA3DD933\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events failures.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205838","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205838","title":"SRG-OS-000472-GPOS-00217","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205838","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000472-GPOS-00217","rule_id_src":"SV-205838r991581_rule","rule_id":"SV-205838","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000180","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit logoff successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Logon/Logoff >> \"Audit Logoff\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nLogon/Logoff >> Logoff - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nLogoff records user logoffs. If this is an interactive logoff, it is recorded on the local system. If it is to a network share, it is recorded on the system accessed.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000472-GPOS-00217, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93171","SV-103259","CCI-000172","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4955","uuid":"6801f88b-147f-407b-af89-bfcfe1d1d766","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D07E149E2DC550CD57A91F62F65E8ACD4C4AC9DE\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit logoff successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205839","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205839","title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205839","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","rule_id_src":"SV-205839r991583_rule","rule_id":"SV-205839","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000130","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Detailed Tracking - Plug and Play Events successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Detailed Tracking >> \"Audit PNP Activity\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDetailed Tracking >> Plug and Play Events - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nPlug and Play activity records events related to the successful connection of external devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93157","SV-103245","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5067","uuid":"6005bb9e-1c81-4cbb-80e3-d980ab6d8312","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B91F51B618F9C015F84A48287BC384338937C034\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Detailed Tracking - Plug and Play Events successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205840","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205840","title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205840","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","rule_id_src":"SV-205840r991583_rule","rule_id":"SV-205840","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000240","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Removable Storage\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nObject Access >> Removable Storage - Success\n\nVirtual machines or systems that use network attached storage may generate excessive audit events for secondary virtual drives or the network attached storage when this setting is enabled. This may be set to Not Configured in such cases and would not be a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nRemovable Storage auditing under Object Access records events related to access attempts on file system objects on removable storage devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103255","V-93167","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8328","uuid":"834797aa-38f5-4d97-a3d8-4dfb5a97e84a","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C8CFF5F6D2CB3B28B24570BCC0F463B1DD3F18A8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205841","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205841","title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205841","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","rule_id_src":"SV-205841r991583_rule","rule_id":"SV-205841","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000250","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Removable Storage\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nObject Access >> Removable Storage - Failure\n\nVirtual machines or systems that use network attached storage may generate excessive audit events for secondary virtual drives or the network attached storage when this setting is enabled. This may be set to Not Configured in such cases and would not be a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nRemovable Storage auditing under Object Access records events related to access attempts on file system objects on removable storage devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103257","V-93169","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"1190","uuid":"152540ba-95ce-40a1-98a5-352a556cbe5b","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0D4DBFDB191216583AC04AD9816048F863036BE5\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage failures.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205842","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205842","title":"SRG-OS-000478-GPOS-00223","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205842","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000478-GPOS-00223","rule_id_src":"SV-205842r1137699_rule","rule_id":"SV-205842","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000360","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to use FIPS-compliant algorithms for encryption, hashing, and signing.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"System cryptography: Use FIPS compliant algorithms for encryption, hashing, and signing\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This is NA if the host is running SharePoint.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\FIPSAlgorithmPolicy\\\n\nValue Name: Enabled\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)\n \nClients with this setting enabled will not be able to communicate via digitally encrypted or signed protocols with servers that do not support these algorithms. Both the browser and web server must be configured to use TLS; otherwise. the browser will not be able to connect to a secure site.\n\nIf the server is hosting SharePoint, this is not applicable.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This setting ensures the system uses algorithms that are FIPS-compliant for encryption, hashing, and signing. FIPS-compliant algorithms meet specific standards established by the U.S. Government and must be the algorithms used for all OS encryption functions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103597","V-93511","CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"3042","uuid":"b58cf34d-1734-4b69-9b60-cdc07206e2c9","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 701F4D377DE1CCAB531A5A9E24A20ADFF11C8C41\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to use FIPS-compliant algorithms for encryption, hashing, and signing.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205843","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205843","title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205843","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","rule_id_src":"SV-205843r959008_rule","rule_id":"SV-205843","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000020","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must, at a minimum, offload audit records of interconnected systems in real time and offload standalone or nondomain-joined systems weekly.","fix_text":"Configure the system to, at a minimum, offload audit records of interconnected systems in real time and offload standalone or nondomain-joined systems weekly.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit records, at a minimum, are offloaded for interconnected systems in real time and offloaded for standalone or nondomain-joined systems weekly. \n\nIf they are not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protection of log data includes ensuring the log data is not accidentally lost or deleted. Audit information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103273","V-93185","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"4448","uuid":"cbcf1a6d-a34c-428a-8b24-5e427fbb4cd2","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 358DDA341AAAEB8FC3CFE4755681B96C7A508C72\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must, at a minimum, offload audit records of interconnected systems in real time and offload standalone or nondomain-joined systems weekly.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205844","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205844","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205844","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205844r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205844","rule_version":"WN19-00-000010","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 users with Administrative privileges must have separate accounts for administrative duties and normal operational tasks.","fix_text":"Ensure each user with administrative privileges has a separate account for user duties and one for privileged duties.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify each user with administrative privileges has been assigned a unique administrative account separate from their standard user account. \n\nIf users with administrative privileges do not have separate accounts for administrative functions and standard user functions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using a privileged account to perform routine functions makes the computer vulnerable to malicious software inadvertently introduced during a session that has been granted full privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93369","SV-103457","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8818","uuid":"bffbde3a-f3e6-402e-a60b-7a7007244ef8","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8FD11D5BD86F5B7690AEDA54DF8DC28C68C409D9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 users with Administrative privileges must have separate accounts for administrative duties and normal operational tasks.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205845","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205845","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205845","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205845r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205845","rule_version":"WN19-00-000030","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 administrative accounts must not be used with applications that access the Internet, such as web browsers, or with potential Internet sources, such as email.","fix_text":"Establish a policy, at minimum, to prohibit administrative accounts from using applications that access the Internet, such as web browsers, or with potential Internet sources, such as email. Ensure the policy is enforced.\n\nThe organization may use technical means such as whitelisting to prevent the use of browsers and mail applications to enforce this requirement.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine whether organization policy, at a minimum, prohibits administrative accounts from using applications that access the Internet, such as web browsers, or with potential Internet sources, such as email, except as necessary for local service administration.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.\n\nThe organization may use technical means such as whitelisting to prevent the use of browsers and mail applications to enforce this requirement.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using applications that access the Internet or have potential Internet sources using administrative privileges exposes a system to compromise. If a flaw in an application is exploited while running as a privileged user, the entire system could be compromised. Web browsers and email are common attack vectors for introducing malicious code and must not be run with an administrative account.\n\nSince administrative accounts may generally change or work around technical restrictions for running a web browser or other applications, it is essential that policy require administrative accounts to not access the Internet or use applications such as email.\n\nThe policy should define specific exceptions for local service administration. These exceptions may include HTTP(S)-based tools that are used for the administration of the local system, services, or attached devices.\n\nWhitelisting can be used to enforce the policy to ensure compliance.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93205","SV-103293","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8023","uuid":"ee375436-1232-4a96-9c23-dce93785aed1","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D2E3D0823F5A2DF13E098EFE90868409EDFD7FFF\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 administrative accounts must not be used with applications that access the Internet, such as web browsers, or with potential Internet sources, such as email.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205846","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205846","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205846","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205846r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205846","rule_version":"WN19-00-000040","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 members of the Backup Operators group must have separate accounts for backup duties and normal operational tasks.","fix_text":"Ensure each member of the Backup Operators group has separate accounts for backup functions and standard user functions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If no accounts are members of the Backup Operators group, this is NA.\n\nVerify users with accounts in the Backup Operators group have a separate user account for backup functions and for performing normal user tasks.\n\nIf users with accounts in the Backup Operators group do not have separate accounts for backup functions and standard user functions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Backup Operators are able to read and write to any file in the system, regardless of the rights assigned to it. Backup and restore rights permit users to circumvent the file access restrictions present on NTFS disk drives for backup and restore purposes. Members of the Backup Operators group must have separate logon accounts for performing backup duties.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93207","SV-103295","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2069","uuid":"d33efc67-6121-4087-8a2b-63ec33ac4e97","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 69AE7D9B01427944868693A2C92AADBF02FA4CBB\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 members of the Backup Operators group must have separate accounts for backup duties and normal operational tasks.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205847","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205847","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205847","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205847r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205847","rule_version":"WN19-00-000060","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 manually managed application account passwords must be changed at least annually or when a system administrator with knowledge of the password leaves the organization.","fix_text":"Change passwords for manually managed application/service accounts at least annually or when an administrator with knowledge of the password leaves the organization.\n\nIt is recommended that system-managed service accounts be used whenever possible.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if manually managed application/service accounts exist. If none exist, this is NA.\n\nIf passwords for manually managed application/service accounts are not changed at least annually or when an administrator with knowledge of the password leaves the organization, this is a finding.\n\nIdentify manually managed application/service accounts.\n\nTo determine the date a password was last changed:\n\nDomain controllers:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"Get-AdUser -Identity [application account name] -Properties PasswordLastSet | FT Name, PasswordLastSet\", where [application account name] is the name of the manually managed application/service account.\n\nIf the \"PasswordLastSet\" date is more than one year old, this is a finding.\n\nMember servers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems:\n\nOpen \"Command Prompt\".\n\nEnter 'Net User [application account name] | Find /i \"Password Last Set\"', where [application account name] is the name of the manually managed application/service account.\n\nIf the \"Password Last Set\" date is more than one year old, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Setting application account passwords to expire may cause applications to stop functioning. However, not changing them on a regular basis exposes them to attack. If managed service accounts are used, this alleviates the need to manually change application account passwords.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103297","V-93209","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8594","uuid":"4c9ae7d6-6fc2-4edc-8235-3f11a91cb4c9","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8438B08EDDECCEFAED7C76B0324DE0904B2FC587\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 manually managed application account passwords must be changed at least annually or when a system administrator with knowledge of the password leaves the organization.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205848","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205848","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205848","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205848r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205848","rule_version":"WN19-00-000090","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 domain-joined systems must have a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) enabled and ready for use.","fix_text":"Ensure domain-joined systems have a TPM that is configured for use. (Versions 2.0 or 1.2 support Credential Guard.)\n\nThe TPM must be enabled in the firmware.\n\nRun \"tpm.msc\" for configuration options in Windows.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nVerify the system has a TPM and it is ready for use.\n\nRun \"tpm.msc\".\n\nReview the sections in the center pane.\n\n\"Status\" must indicate it has been configured with a message such as \"The TPM is ready for use\" or \"The TPM is on and ownership has been taken\".\n\nTPM Manufacturer Information - Specific Version = 2.0 or 1.2\n\nIf a TPM is not found or is not ready for use, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Credential Guard uses virtualization-based security to protect data that could be used in credential theft attacks if compromised. A number of system requirements must be met in order for Credential Guard to be configured and enabled properly. Without a TPM enabled and ready for use, Credential Guard keys are stored in a less secure method using software.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93213","SV-103301","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8505","uuid":"d52c8f56-5693-4289-b0da-8b92e7ce9c36","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E2955A25619F844B409A5AADAA9FCFE6378EC951\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 domain-joined systems must have a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) enabled and ready for use.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205849","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205849","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205849","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205849r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205849","rule_version":"WN19-00-000100","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be maintained at a supported servicing level.","fix_text":"Update the system to a Version 1809 (Build 17763.xxx) or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Open \"Command Prompt\".\n\nEnter \"winver.exe\".\n\nIf the \"About Windows\" dialog box does not display \"Microsoft Windows Server Version 1809 (Build 17763.xxx)\" or greater, this is a finding.\n\nPreview versions must not be used in a production environment.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Systems at unsupported servicing levels will not receive security updates for new vulnerabilities, which leave them subject to exploitation. Systems must be maintained at a servicing level supported by the vendor with new security updates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103303","V-93215","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8846","uuid":"d2421722-1fd1-414a-8807-408c865f1855","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 66EC91140003305E9CCF11D1E426FD54F133277B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be maintained at a supported servicing level.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205850","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205850","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205850","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205850r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205850","rule_version":"WN19-00-000110","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must use an anti-virus program.","fix_text":"If no anti-virus software is in use, install Windows Defender or third-party anti-virus.\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"Install-WindowsFeature -Name Windows-Defender\u201d.\n\nFor third-party anti-virus, install per anti-virus instructions and disable Windows Defender.\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"Uninstall-WindowsFeature -Name Windows-Defender\u201d.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify an anti-virus solution is installed on the system. The anti-virus solution may be bundled with an approved host-based security solution.\n\nIf there is no anti-virus solution installed on the system, this is a finding.\n\nVerify if Windows Defender is in use or enabled:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \u201cget-service | where {$_.DisplayName -Like \"*Defender*\"} | Select Status,DisplayName\u201d\n\nVerify if third-party anti-virus is in use or enabled:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"get-service | where {$_.DisplayName -Like \"*mcafee*\"} | Select Status,DisplayName\u201d\n\nEnter \"get-service | where {$_.DisplayName -Like \"*symantec*\"} | Select Status,DisplayName\u201d","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Malicious software can establish a base on individual desktops and servers. Employing an automated mechanism to detect this type of software will aid in elimination of the software from the operating system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103305","V-93217","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7762","uuid":"490b1293-4558-4476-88a6-5a670064dbda","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D43DB5EE9A6DB3B955A187E26170986AE2B788BD\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must use an anti-virus program.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205851","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205851","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205851","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205851r1186378_rule","rule_id":"SV-205851","rule_version":"WN19-00-000120","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must have a host-based intrusion detection and prevention service installed.","fix_text":"Install a HIDS and HIPS on each server.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if there is a HIDS and HIPS on each server. \n\nA HIDS device is not required on a system that has the role as the Network Intrusion Device (NID). However, this exception needs to be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).\n\nIf a HIDS and HIPS are not installed on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A properly configured Host-based Intrusion Detection System (HIDS) and Host-based Intrusion Prevention System (HIPS) provides another level of defense against unauthorized access to critical servers. With proper configuration and logging enabled, such a system can stop and/or alert for many attempts to gain unauthorized access to resources.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103307","V-93219","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5704","uuid":"4ead779f-65b1-428b-8bfa-e7cd540c7aea","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EB788174B65F27F4DC6BF9EFC8C8C34B3B11AE62\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must have a host-based intrusion detection and prevention service installed.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205852","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205852","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205852","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205852r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205852","rule_version":"WN19-00-000240","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must have software certificate installation files removed.","fix_text":"Remove any certificate installation files (*.p12 and *.pfx) found on a system.\n\nNote: This does not apply to server-based applications that have a requirement for .p12 certificate files or Adobe PreFlight certificate files.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Search all drives for *.p12 and *.pfx files.\n\nIf any files with these extensions exist, this is a finding.\n\nThis does not apply to server-based applications that have a requirement for .p12 certificate files or Adobe PreFlight certificate files. Some applications create files with extensions of .p12 that are not certificate installation files. Removal of non-certificate installation files from systems is not required. These must be documented with the ISSO.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of software certificates and their accompanying installation files for end users to access resources is less secure than the use of hardware-based certificates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93221","SV-103309","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8441","uuid":"b89e1591-178c-42a2-a77f-227788abb7e4","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F9E782B4D112ECFF5A76EC73EEF38DAFC563D658\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must have software certificate installation files removed.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205853","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205853","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205853","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205853r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205853","rule_version":"WN19-00-000420","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 FTP servers must be configured to prevent anonymous logons.","fix_text":"Configure the FTP service to prevent anonymous logons.\n\nOpen \"Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager\".\n\nSelect the server.\n\nDouble-click \"FTP Authentication\".\n\nSelect \"Anonymous Authentication\".\n\nSelect \"Disabled\" under \"Actions\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If FTP is not installed on the system, this is NA.\n\nOpen \"Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager\".\n\nSelect the server.\n\nDouble-click \"FTP Authentication\".\n\nIf the \"Anonymous Authentication\" status is \"Enabled\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The FTP service allows remote users to access shared files and directories. Allowing anonymous FTP connections makes user auditing difficult.\n\nUsing accounts that have administrator privileges to log on to FTP risks that the userid and password will be captured on the network and give administrator access to an unauthorized user.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93223","SV-103311","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1661","uuid":"e6ab670a-a9fb-4c03-8258-9f9a9f19f143","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C94F86026FB33DD19EC0811E0BF18C504B928C52\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 FTP servers must be configured to prevent anonymous logons.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205854","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205854","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205854","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205854r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205854","rule_version":"WN19-00-000430","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 FTP servers must be configured to prevent access to the system drive.","fix_text":"Configure the FTP sites to allow access only to specific FTP shared resources. Do not allow access to other areas of the system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If FTP is not installed on the system, this is NA.\n\nOpen \"Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager\".\n\nSelect \"Sites\" under the server name.\n\nFor any sites with a Binding that lists FTP, right-click the site and select \"Explore\".\n\nIf the site is not defined to a specific folder for shared FTP resources, this is a finding.\n\nIf the site includes any system areas such as root of the drive, Program Files, or Windows directories, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The FTP service allows remote users to access shared files and directories that could provide access to system resources and compromise the system, especially if the user can gain access to the root directory of the boot drive.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93225","SV-103313","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7591","uuid":"fadefa6a-f705-4de3-af3a-4f1765a7578c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CF02680F38BB63874CA4D0F68CDA5021DD3673F2\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 FTP servers must be configured to prevent access to the system drive.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205855","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205855","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205855","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205855r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205855","rule_version":"WN19-00-000450","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must have orphaned security identifiers (SIDs) removed from user rights.","fix_text":"Remove any unresolved SIDs found in User Rights assignments and determined to not be for currently valid accounts or groups by removing the accounts or groups from the appropriate group policy.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the effective User Rights setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nReview each User Right listed for any unresolved SIDs to determine whether they are valid, such as due to being temporarily disconnected from the domain. (Unresolved SIDs have the format that begins with \"*S-1-\".)\n\nIf any unresolved SIDs exist and are not for currently valid accounts or groups, this is a finding.\n\nFor server core installations, run the following command:\n\nSecedit /export /areas USER_RIGHTS /cfg c:\\path\\UserRights.txt\n\nThe results in the file identify user right assignments by SID instead of group name. Review the SIDs for unidentified ones. A list of typical SIDs \\ Groups is below, search Microsoft for articles on well-known SIDs for others. \n\nIf any unresolved SIDs exist and are not for currently valid accounts or groups, this is a finding.\n\nSID - Group\nS-1-5-11 - Authenticated Users\nS-1-5-113 - Local account\nS-1-5-114 - Local account and member of Administrators group\nS-1-5-19 - Local Service\nS-1-5-20 - Network Service\nS-1-5-32-544 - Administrators\nS-1-5-32-546 - Guests\nS-1-5-6 - Service\nS-1-5-9 - Enterprise Domain Controllers\nS-1-5-domain-512 - Domain Admins\nS-1-5-root domain-519 - Enterprise Admins\nS-1-5-80-3139157870-2983391045-3678747466-658725712-1809340420 - NT Service\\WdiServiceHost","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Accounts or groups given rights on a system may show up as unresolved SIDs for various reasons including deletion of the accounts or groups.  If the account or group objects are reanimated, there is a potential they may still have rights no longer intended.  Valid domain accounts or groups may also show up as unresolved SIDs if a connection to the domain cannot be established for some reason.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93227","SV-103315","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6006","uuid":"e48b04de-c2c4-4fd9-87f3-ac23889027c5","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 081A24DFAED9BC39D68FD88DF1C1D1D566B11C78\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must have orphaned security identifiers (SIDs) removed from user rights.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205856","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205856","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205856","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205856r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205856","rule_version":"WN19-00-000460","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 systems must have Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) firmware and be configured to run in UEFI mode, not Legacy BIOS.","fix_text":"Configure UEFI firmware to run in \"UEFI\" mode, not \"Legacy BIOS\" mode.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Some older systems may not have UEFI firmware. This is currently a CAT III; it will be raised in severity at a future date when broad support of Windows hardware and firmware requirements are expected to be met. Devices that have UEFI firmware must run in \"UEFI\" mode.\n\nVerify the system firmware is configured to run in \"UEFI\" mode, not \"Legacy BIOS\".\n\nRun \"System Information\".\n\nUnder \"System Summary\", if \"BIOS Mode\" does not display \"UEFI\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"UEFI provides additional security features in comparison to legacy BIOS firmware, including Secure Boot. UEFI is required to support additional security features in Windows, including Virtualization Based Security and Credential Guard. Systems with UEFI that are operating in \"Legacy BIOS\" mode will not support these security features.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93229","SV-103317","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2372","uuid":"10099469-1d23-462d-8c16-617f26b97a4c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EC9A6CCE96C58CBF2C88557C1D2725D0C290FA7C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 systems must have Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) firmware and be configured to run in UEFI mode, not Legacy BIOS.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205857","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205857","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205857","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205857r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205857","rule_version":"WN19-00-000470","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must have Secure Boot enabled.","fix_text":"Enable Secure Boot in the system firmware.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Some older systems may not have UEFI firmware. This is currently a CAT III; it will be raised in severity at a future date when broad support of Windows hardware and firmware requirements are expected to be met. Devices that have UEFI firmware must have Secure Boot enabled.  \n\nRun \"System Information\".\n\nUnder \"System Summary\", if \"Secure Boot State\" does not display \"On\", this is a finding.\n\nOn server core installations, run the following PowerShell command:\n\nConfirm-SecureBootUEFI\n\nIf a value of \"True\" is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Secure Boot is a standard that ensures systems boot only to a trusted operating system. Secure Boot is required to support additional security features in Windows, including Virtualization Based Security and Credential Guard. If Secure Boot is turned off, these security features will not function.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103319","V-93231","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4797","uuid":"96cb5918-d05a-48a4-84a2-e625a405b3b3","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2A3CFA57BB41BD2A3F3D35E6EBB7CF11682D3C41\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must have Secure Boot enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205858","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205858","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205858","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205858r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205858","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000030","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) source routing must be configured to the highest protection level to prevent IP source routing.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MSS (Legacy) >> \"MSS: (DisableIPSourceRouting IPv6) IP source routing protection level (protects against packet spoofing)\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Highest protection, source routing is completely disabled\" selected.\n\nThis policy setting requires the installation of the MSS-Legacy custom templates included with the STIG package. \"MSS-Legacy.admx\" and \"MSS-Legacy.adml\" must be copied to the \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions and \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions\\en-US directories respectively.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Tcpip6\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: DisableIPSourceRouting\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000002 (2)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the system to disable IPv6 source routing protects against spoofing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103321","V-93233","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1931","uuid":"aa72c723-9da9-4e2a-b263-6eff9a6863df","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 765D84C936878E287F72D974CCE7B2173811E1AE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) source routing must be configured to the highest protection level to prevent IP source routing.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205859","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205859","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205859","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205859r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205859","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000040","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 source routing must be configured to the highest protection level to prevent Internet Protocol (IP) source routing.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MSS (Legacy) >> \"MSS: (DisableIPSourceRouting) IP source routing protection level (protects against packet spoofing)\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Highest protection, source routing is completely disabled\" selected.\n\nThis policy setting requires the installation of the MSS-Legacy custom templates included with the STIG package. \"MSS-Legacy.admx\" and \"MSS-Legacy.adml\" must be copied to the \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions and \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions\\en-US directories respectively.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Tcpip\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: DisableIPSourceRouting\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000002 (2)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the system to disable IP source routing protects against spoofing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103323","V-93235","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5337","uuid":"ed8238fb-7ce0-4d75-a98a-c8ca40049f7e","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6F0A5FFA1ADC71CC9070E2DEB2B763AC3EF5839B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 source routing must be configured to the highest protection level to prevent Internet Protocol (IP) source routing.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205860","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205860","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205860","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205860r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205860","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000050","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to prevent Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects from overriding Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)-generated routes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MSS (Legacy) >> \"MSS: (EnableICMPRedirect) Allow ICMP redirects to override OSPF generated routes\" to \"Disabled\".\n\nThis policy setting requires the installation of the MSS-Legacy custom templates included with the STIG package. \"MSS-Legacy.admx\" and \"MSS-Legacy.adml\" must be copied to the \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions and \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions\\en-US directories respectively.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Tcpip\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: EnableICMPRedirect\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing ICMP redirect of routes can lead to traffic not being routed properly. When disabled, this forces ICMP to be routed via the shortest path first.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103325","V-93237","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3586","uuid":"28455def-083f-4182-a968-8325bf31420f","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205861","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205861","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205861","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205861r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205861","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000070","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 insecure logons to an SMB server must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Network >> Lanman Workstation >> \"Enable insecure guest logons\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\LanmanWorkstation\\\n\nValue Name: AllowInsecureGuestAuth\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Insecure guest logons allow unauthenticated access to shared folders. Shared resources on a system must require authentication to establish proper access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103327","V-93239","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6635","uuid":"39b35787-a0b3-41e3-a0ff-45f228845c32","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205862","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205862","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205862","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205862r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205862","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000080","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 hardened Universal Naming Convention (UNC) paths must be defined to require mutual authentication and integrity for at least the \\\\*\\SYSVOL and \\\\*\\NETLOGON shares.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Network >> Network Provider >> \"Hardened UNC Paths\" to \"Enabled\" with at least the following configured in \"Hardened UNC Paths\" (click the \"Show\" button to display):\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\SYSVOL\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\NETLOGON\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This requirement is applicable to domain-joined systems. For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry values do not exist or are not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\NetworkProvider\\HardenedPaths\\\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\NETLOGON\nValue Type: REG_SZ\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1\n\nValue Name: \\\\*\\SYSVOL\nValue Type: REG_SZ\nValue: RequireMutualAuthentication=1, RequireIntegrity=1\n\nAdditional entries would not be a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Additional security requirements are applied to UNC paths specified in hardened UNC paths before allowing access to them. This aids in preventing tampering with or spoofing of connections to these paths.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103329","V-93241","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3193","uuid":"bd954b67-cad3-4be1-85fd-fba9d80a9c1e","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6F5EFA213D8250491D54B68ABC3597EE1BD13CF0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 hardened Universal Naming Convention (UNC) paths must be defined to require mutual authentication and integrity for at least the \\\\*\\SYSVOL and \\\\*\\NETLOGON shares.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205863","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205863","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205863","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205863r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205863","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000100","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to enable Remote host allows delegation of non-exportable credentials.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Credentials Delegation >> \"Remote host allows delegation of non-exportable credentials\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CredentialsDelegation\\\n\nValue Name: AllowProtectedCreds\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An exportable version of credentials is provided to remote hosts when using credential delegation which exposes them to theft on the remote host.  Restricted Admin mode or Remote Credential Guard allow delegation of non-exportable credentials providing additional protection of the credentials.  Enabling this configures the host to support Restricted Admin mode or Remote Credential Guard.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93243","SV-103331","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1750","uuid":"4ba75785-6398-429a-8f0c-98b6dedb7591","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4EF516E27F40E3C958648E8128E1F5BCC43C56B6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to enable Remote host allows delegation of non-exportable credentials.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205864","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205864","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205864","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205864r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205864","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000110","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 virtualization-based security must be enabled with the platform security level configured to Secure Boot or Secure Boot with DMA Protection.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Device Guard >> \"Turn On Virtualization Based Security\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Secure Boot\" or \"Secure Boot and DMA Protection\" selected.\n\nA Microsoft TechNet article on Credential Guard, including system requirement details, can be found at the following link:\n\nhttps://technet.microsoft.com/itpro/windows/keep-secure/credential-guard","weight":"10.0","check_content":"For standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" with elevated privileges (run as administrator).\n\nEnter the following:\n\n\"Get-CimInstance -ClassName Win32_DeviceGuard -Namespace root\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeviceGuard\"\n\nIf \"RequiredSecurityProperties\" does not include a value of \"2\" indicating \"Secure Boot\" (e.g., \"{1, 2}\"), this is a finding.\n\nIf \"Secure Boot and DMA Protection\" is configured, \"3\" will also be displayed in the results (e.g., \"{1, 2, 3}\").\n\nIf \"VirtualizationBasedSecurityStatus\" is not a value of \"2\" indicating \"Running\", this is a finding.\n\nAlternately:\n\nRun \"System Information\".\n\nUnder \"System Summary\", verify the following:\n\nIf \"Virtualization based security\" does not display \"Running\", this is a finding.\n\nIf \"Virtualization based Required security Properties\" does not display \"Base Virtualization Support, Secure Boot\", this is a finding.\n\nIf \"Secure Boot and DMA Protection\" is configured, \"DMA Protection\" will also be displayed (e.g., \"Base Virtualization Support, Secure Boot, DMA Protection\").\n\nThe policy settings referenced in the Fix section will configure the following registry values. However, due to hardware requirements, the registry values alone do not ensure proper function.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeviceGuard\\\n\nValue Name: EnableVirtualizationBasedSecurity\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)\n\nValue Name: RequirePlatformSecurityFeatures\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1) (Secure Boot only) or 0x00000003 (3) (Secure Boot and DMA Protection)\n\nA Microsoft TechNet article on Credential Guard, including system requirement details, can be found at the following link:\n\nhttps://technet.microsoft.com/itpro/windows/keep-secure/credential-guard","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Virtualization-based security (VBS) provides the platform for the additional security features Credential Guard and virtualization-based protection of code integrity. Secure Boot is the minimum security level, with DMA protection providing additional memory protection. DMA Protection requires a CPU that supports input/output memory management unit (IOMMU).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93245","SV-103333","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4536","uuid":"bce8cbea-df8f-4ea2-a2b9-51e036aac958","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 517F6A93827C529F4B5490577DE5D75BC0B8EF7F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 virtualization-based security must be enabled with the platform security level configured to Secure Boot or Secure Boot with DMA Protection.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205865","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205865","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205865","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205865r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205865","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000130","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Early Launch Antimalware, Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy must prevent boot drivers identified as bad.","fix_text":"The default behavior is for Early Launch Antimalware - Boot-Start Driver Initialization policy to enforce \"Good, unknown and bad but critical\" (preventing \"bad\").\n\nIf this needs to be corrected or a more secure setting is desired, configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Early Launch Antimalware >> \"Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy\" to \"Not Configured\" or \"Enabled\" with any option other than \"All\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The default behavior is for Early Launch Antimalware - Boot-Start Driver Initialization policy to enforce \"Good, unknown and bad but critical\" (preventing \"bad\").\n\nIf the registry value name below does not exist, this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"0x00000007 (7)\", this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Policies\\EarlyLaunch\\\n\nValue Name: DriverLoadPolicy\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1), 0x00000003 (3), or 0x00000008 (8) (or if the Value Name does not exist)\n\nPossible values for this setting are:\n8 - Good only\n1 - Good and unknown\n3 - Good, unknown and bad but critical\n7 - All (which includes \"bad\" and would be a finding)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Compromised boot drivers can introduce malware prior to protection mechanisms that load after initialization. The Early Launch Antimalware driver can limit allowed drivers based on classifications determined by the malware protection application. At a minimum, drivers determined to be bad must not be allowed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93249","SV-103337","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6491","uuid":"351a32c5-20d3-4a69-9f07-831dd17ed6a1","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 64EE5E87E75034E7223843FE62FB11ED9DA6D5C8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 Early Launch Antimalware, Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy must prevent boot drivers identified as bad.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205866","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205866","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205866","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205866r1135352_rule","rule_id":"SV-205866","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000140","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 group policy objects must be reprocessed even if they have not changed.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Group Policy >> \"Configure registry policy processing\" to \"Enabled\" with the option \"Process even if the Group Policy objects have not changed\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This requirement is not applicable for Domain Controllers.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Group Policy\\{35378EAC-683F-11D2-A89A-00C04FBBCFA2}\\\n\nValue Name: NoGPOListChanges\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Registry entries for group policy settings can potentially be changed from the required configuration. This could occur as part of troubleshooting or by a malicious process on a compromised system. Enabling this setting and then selecting the \"Process even if the Group Policy objects have not changed\" option ensures the policies will be reprocessed even if none have been changed. This way, any unauthorized changes are forced to match the domain-based group policy settings again.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93251","SV-103339","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9691","uuid":"0a972da9-f86c-41da-b170-37ff61ee9ab5","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 63326BA8AE4B3C1361133CA610E103617D1B3759\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 group policy objects must be reprocessed even if they have not changed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205867","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205867","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205867","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205867r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205867","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000180","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 users must be prompted to authenticate when the system wakes from sleep (on battery).","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Power Management >> Sleep Settings >> \"Require a password when a computer wakes (on battery)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Power\\PowerSettings\\0e796bdb-100d-47d6-a2d5-f7d2daa51f51\\\n\nValue Name: DCSettingIndex\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A system that does not require authentication when resuming from sleep may provide access to unauthorized users. Authentication must always be required when accessing a system. This setting ensures users are prompted for a password when the system wakes from sleep (on battery).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93253","SV-103341","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8449","uuid":"3397ffc0-8a4b-4c6c-b482-0959e129a9cc","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 21762BAEBFC7A083A64B38A863983AA3CA6E192E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 users must be prompted to authenticate when the system wakes from sleep (on battery).' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205868","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205868","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205868","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205868r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205868","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000190","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 users must be prompted to authenticate when the system wakes from sleep (plugged in).","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Power Management >> Sleep Settings >> \"Require a password when a computer wakes (plugged in)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Power\\PowerSettings\\0e796bdb-100d-47d6-a2d5-f7d2daa51f51\\\n\nValue Name: ACSettingIndex\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A system that does not require authentication when resuming from sleep may provide access to unauthorized users. Authentication must always be required when accessing a system. This setting ensures users are prompted for a password when the system wakes from sleep (plugged in).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93255","SV-103343","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3704","uuid":"616f191d-da49-4f3a-b1f5-5f40cbe4f0f8","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6B7BDAD95326AA85F96376167758D922A0770656\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 users must be prompted to authenticate when the system wakes from sleep (plugged in).' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205869","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205869","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205869","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205869r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205869","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000250","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Telemetry must be configured to Security or Basic.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Data Collection >> \"Allow Telemetry\" to \"Enabled\" with \"0 - Security [Enterprise Only]\" or \"1 - Basic\" selected in \"Options\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DataCollection\\\n\nValue Name: AllowTelemetry\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0) (Security), 0x00000001 (1) (Basic)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Some features may communicate with the vendor, sending system information or downloading data or components for the feature. Limiting this capability will prevent potentially sensitive information from being sent outside the enterprise. The \"Security\" option for Telemetry configures the lowest amount of data, effectively none outside of the Malicious Software Removal Tool (MSRT), Defender, and telemetry client settings. \"Basic\" sends basic diagnostic and usage data and may be required to support some Microsoft services.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103345","V-93257","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2435","uuid":"cbb1a1dc-260f-4c8d-ade6-3a7784ba13af","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6B267006F0B9E95F76C853CA8E01882ED0FF438E\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 Telemetry must be configured to Security or Basic.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205870","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205870","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205870","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205870r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205870","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000260","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Update must not obtain updates from other PCs on the Internet.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Delivery Optimization >> \"Download Mode\" to \"Enabled\" with any option except \"Internet\" selected.\n\nAcceptable selections include:\n\nBypass (100)\nGroup (2)\nHTTP only (0)\nLAN (1)\nSimple (99)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeliveryOptimization\\\n\nValue Name: DODownloadMode\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0) - No peering (HTTP Only)\n0x00000001 (1) - Peers on same NAT only (LAN)\n0x00000002 (2) - Local Network / Private group peering (Group)\n0x00000063 (99) - Simple download mode, no peering (Simple)\n0x00000064 (100) - Bypass mode, Delivery Optimization not used (Bypass)\n\nA value of 0x00000003 (3), Internet, is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Windows Update can obtain updates from additional sources instead of Microsoft. In addition to Microsoft, updates can be obtained from and sent to PCs on the local network as well as on the Internet. This is part of the Windows Update trusted process, however to minimize outside exposure, obtaining updates from or sending to systems on the Internet must be prevented.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103347","V-93259","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4092","uuid":"904d63b7-883b-47a9-9e87-d513d0d2ae2a","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DDCF53F0B2230A274EA0956FCE78C0CCB254EE95\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 Windows Update must not obtain updates from other PCs on the Internet.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205871","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205871","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205871","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205871r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205871","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000320","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Turning off File Explorer heap termination on corruption must be disabled.","fix_text":"The default behavior is for File Explorer heap termination on corruption to be disabled.\n\nIf this needs to be corrected, configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> File Explorer >> \"Turn off heap termination on corruption\" to \"Not Configured\" or \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The default behavior is for File Explorer heap termination on corruption to be enabled.\n\nIf the registry Value Name below does not exist, this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"0\", this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"1\", this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoHeapTerminationOnCorruption\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0) (or if the Value Name does not exist)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Legacy plug-in applications may continue to function when a File Explorer session has become corrupt. Disabling this feature will prevent this.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93261","SV-103349","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2870","uuid":"9e5c8cc5-9625-4b21-bb31-cb7ebadfc5a6","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205872","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205872","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205872","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205872r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205872","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000330","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 File Explorer shell protocol must run in protected mode.","fix_text":"The default behavior is for shell protected mode to be turned on for File Explorer.\n\nIf this needs to be corrected, configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> File Explorer >> \"Turn off shell protocol protected mode\" to \"Not Configured\" or \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The default behavior is for shell protected mode to be turned on for File Explorer.\n\nIf the registry value name below does not exist, this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"0\", this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"1\", this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: PreXPSP2ShellProtocolBehavior\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0) (or if the Value Name does not exist)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The shell protocol will limit the set of folders that applications can open when run in protected mode. Restricting files an application can open to a limited set of folders increases the security of Windows.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93263","SV-103351","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7858","uuid":"eb6bb38b-8cc1-464f-ac71-e5da4b5198d4","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 88F3FBA0C68E18FFE7DB210BAD03AE22C7B89B6E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 File Explorer shell protocol must run in protected mode.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205873","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205873","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205873","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205873r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205873","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000390","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must prevent attachments from being downloaded from RSS feeds.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> RSS Feeds >> \"Prevent downloading of enclosures\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Internet Explorer\\Feeds\\\n\nValue Name: DisableEnclosureDownload\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Attachments from RSS feeds may not be secure. This setting will prevent attachments from being downloaded from RSS feeds.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93265","SV-103353","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9365","uuid":"3f815daf-25bf-4b14-ad46-8f0414c25525","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205874","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205874","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205874","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205874r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205874","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000440","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 users must be notified if a web-based program attempts to install software.","fix_text":"The default behavior is for Internet Explorer to warn users and select whether to allow or refuse installation when a web-based program attempts to install software on the system.\n\nIf this needs to be corrected, configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Installer >> \"Prevent Internet Explorer security prompt for Windows Installer scripts\" to \"Not Configured\" or \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The default behavior is for Internet Explorer to warn users and select whether to allow or refuse installation when a web-based program attempts to install software on the system.\n\nIf the registry value name below does not exist, this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"0\", this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"1\", this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\\n\nValue Name: SafeForScripting\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0) (or if the Value Name does not exist)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Web-based programs may attempt to install malicious software on a system. Ensuring users are notified if a web-based program attempts to install software allows them to refuse the installation.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103355","V-93267","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1044","uuid":"238ed2d6-ff03-4074-bb4d-e346ecd8ddbb","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A03A90BF72FF8A3470B1B5DC2B17DD755F037C35\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 users must be notified if a web-based program attempts to install software.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205875","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205875","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205875","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205875r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205875","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000150","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 directory data (outside the root DSE) of a non-public directory must be configured to prevent anonymous access.","fix_text":"Configure directory data (outside the root DSE) of a non-public directory to prevent anonymous access.\n\nFor AD, there are multiple configuration items that could enable anonymous access.\n\nChanging the access permissions on the domain naming context object (from the secure defaults) could enable anonymous access. If the check procedures indicate this is the cause, the process that was used to change the permissions should be reversed. This could have been through the Windows Support Tools ADSI Edit console (adsiedit.msc).\n\nThe dsHeuristics option is used. This is addressed in check V-8555 in the AD Forest STIG.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nOpen \"Command Prompt\" (not elevated).\n\nRun \"ldp.exe\".\n\nFrom the \"Connection menu\", select \"Bind\".\n\nClear the User, Password, and Domain fields.\n\nSelect \"Simple bind\" for the Bind type and click \"OK\".\n\nConfirmation of anonymous access will be displayed at the end:\n\nres = ldap_simple_bind_s\nAuthenticated as: 'NT AUTHORITY\\ANONYMOUS LOGON'\n\nFrom the \"Browse\" menu, select \"Search\".\n\nIn the Search dialog, enter the DN of the domain naming context (generally something like \"dc=disaost,dc=mil\") in the Base DN field.\n\nClear the Attributes field and select \"Run\".\n\nError messages should display related to Bind and user not authenticated.\n\nIf attribute data is displayed, anonymous access is enabled to the domain naming context and this is a finding.\n\nThe following network controls allow the finding severity to be downgraded to a CAT II since these measures lower the risk associated with anonymous access.\n\nNetwork hardware ports at the site are subject to 802.1x authentication or MAC address restrictions. \n\nPremise firewall or host restrictions prevent access to ports 389, 636, 3268, and 3269 from client hosts not explicitly identified by domain (.mil) or IP address.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To the extent that anonymous access to directory data (outside the root DSE) is permitted, read access control of the data is effectively disabled. If other means of controlling access (such as network restrictions) are compromised, there may be nothing else to protect the confidentiality of sensitive directory data.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103359","V-93271","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7125","uuid":"58d65afc-509c-48cd-8999-4c489a85c8c7","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A6801AFCA9664546B5A38F8ED27EAA9529178F6E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 directory data (outside the root DSE) of a non-public directory must be configured to prevent anonymous access.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205876","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205876","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205876","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205876r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205876","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000330","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 domain controllers must be configured to allow reset of machine account passwords.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain controller: Refuse machine account password changes\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: RefusePasswordChange\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling this setting on all domain controllers in a domain prevents domain members from changing their computer account passwords. If these passwords are weak or compromised, the inability to change them may leave these computers vulnerable.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93273","SV-103361","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6837","uuid":"cc6243a9-9201-41cc-8f85-22203715481e","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205877","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205877","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205877","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205877r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205877","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000430","rule_title":"The password for the krbtgt account on a domain must be reset at least every 180 days.","fix_text":"Reset the password for the krbtgt account a least every 180 days. The password must be changed twice to effectively remove the password history. Changing once, waiting for replication to complete and changing again reduces the risk of issues. Changing twice in rapid succession forces clients to reauthenticate (including application services) but is desired if a compromise is suspected.\n\nPowerShell scripts are available to accomplish this such as at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/97108/resetting-the-krbtgt-account-password-in-a-domain.html\n\nAll scripts should be tested.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nSelect \"Advanced Features\" in the \"View\" menu if not previously selected.\n\nSelect the \"Users\" node.\n\nRight-click on the krbtgt account and select \"Reset password\".\n\nEnter a password that meets password complexity requirements.\n\nClear the \"User must change password at next logon\" check box.\n\nThe system will automatically change this to a system-generated complex password.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This requirement is applicable to domain controllers; it is NA for other systems. \n\nOpen \"Windows PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"Get-ADUser krbtgt -Property PasswordLastSet\".\n\nIf the \"PasswordLastSet\" date is more than 180 days old, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The krbtgt account acts as a service account for the Kerberos Key Distribution Center (KDC) service.  The account and password are created when a domain is created and the password is typically not changed.  If the krbtgt account is compromised, attackers can create valid Kerberos Ticket Granting Tickets (TGT).\n\nThe password must be changed twice to effectively remove the password history. Changing once, waiting for replication to complete and the amount of time equal to or greater than the maximum Kerberos ticket lifetime, and changing again reduces the risk of issues.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93211","SV-103299","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4630","uuid":"6957cd34-922c-4876-91db-03eeabdd2fa5","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4AC47425BF836B3BAAF7FDD69F98A09BBD80D6A8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The password for the krbtgt account on a domain must be reset at least every 180 days.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205906","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205906","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205906","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205906r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205906","rule_version":"WN19-MS-000050","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must limit the caching of logon credentials to four or less on domain-joined member servers.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Interactive Logon: Number of previous logons to cache (in case Domain Controller is not available)\" to \"4\" logons or less.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to member servers. For domain controllers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Winlogon\\\n\nValue Name:  CachedLogonsCount\n\nValue Type:  REG_SZ\nValue:  4 (or less)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The default Windows configuration caches the last logon credentials for users who log on interactively to a system. This feature is provided for system availability reasons, such as the user's machine being disconnected from the network or domain controllers being unavailable. Even though the credential cache is well protected, if a system is attacked, an unauthorized individual may isolate the password to a domain user account using a password-cracking program and gain access to the domain.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103363","V-93275","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4212","uuid":"96610a84-ed8a-47ff-966c-c91fbd16962e","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4748C4E7E068DF098110F751D59A04796A233035\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must limit the caching of logon credentials to four or less on domain-joined member servers.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205907","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205907","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205907","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205907r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205907","rule_version":"WN19-MS-000140","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be running Credential Guard on domain-joined member servers.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Device Guard >> \"Turn On Virtualization Based Security\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Enabled with UEFI lock\" selected for \"Credential Guard Configuration\".\n\nA Microsoft article on Credential Guard system requirement can be found at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/credential-guard/credential-guard-requirements\n\nSeverity Override Guidance: The AO can allow the severity override if they have reviewed the overall protection provided to the affected servers that are not capable of complying with the Credential Guard requirement. Items that should be reviewed/considered for compliance or mitigation for non-Credential Guard compliance are:\n\nThe use of Microsoft Local Administrator Password Solution (LAPS) or similar products to control different local administrative passwords for all affected servers. This is to include a strict password change requirement (60 days or less).\n\u2026.\nStrict separation of roles and duties. Server administrator credentials cannot be used on Windows 10 desktop to administer it. Documentation of all exceptions should be supplied.\n\u2026.\nUse of a Privileged Access Workstation (PAW) and adherence to the Clean Source principle for administering affected servers. \n\u2026.\nBoundary Protection that is currently in place to protect from vulnerabilities in the network/servers.\n\u2026.\nWindows Defender rule block credential stealing from LSASS.exe is applied.  This rule can only be applied if Windows Defender is in use.\n\u2026.\nThe overall number of vulnerabilities that are unmitigated on the network/servers.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"For domain controllers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems, this is NA.\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" with elevated privileges (run as administrator).\n\nEnter the following:\n\n\"Get-CimInstance -ClassName Win32_DeviceGuard -Namespace root\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeviceGuard\"\n\nIf \"SecurityServicesRunning\" does not include a value of \"1\" (e.g., \"{1, 2}\"), this is a finding.\n\nAlternately:\n\nRun \"System Information\".\n\nUnder \"System Summary\", verify the following:\n\nIf \"Device Guard Security Services Running\" does not list \"Credential Guard\", this is a finding.\n\nThe policy settings referenced in the Fix section will configure the following registry value. However, due to hardware requirements, the registry value alone does not ensure proper function.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\DeviceGuard\\\n\nValue Name: LsaCfgFlags\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1) (Enabled with UEFI lock)\n\nA Microsoft article on Credential Guard system requirement can be found at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/credential-guard/credential-guard-requirements","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Credential Guard uses virtualization-based security to protect data that could be used in credential theft attacks if compromised. This authentication information, which was stored in the Local Security Authority (LSA) in previous versions of Windows, is isolated from the rest of operating system and can only be accessed by privileged system software.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93277","SV-103365","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6504","uuid":"ed5d4716-1e02-4ba0-a6fc-f0732f03b5a7","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5919A1664B2373894CF81F6A2B8C2F0787129B18\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be running Credential Guard on domain-joined member servers.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205908","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205908","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205908","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205908r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205908","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000020","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must prevent local accounts with blank passwords from being used from the network.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Accounts: Limit local account use of blank passwords to console logon only\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\\n\nValue Name: LimitBlankPasswordUse\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An account without a password can allow unauthorized access to a system as only the username would be required. Password policies should prevent accounts with blank passwords from existing on a system. However, if a local account with a blank password does exist, enabling this setting will prevent network access, limiting the account to local console logon only.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93279","SV-103367","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6969","uuid":"5c40aab7-0cac-47d3-9d58-a0e9e5c8a9e2","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F508FFD1E371986320A14B7FD2E13E6726CC1561\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must prevent local accounts with blank passwords from being used from the network.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205909","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205909","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205909","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205909r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205909","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000030","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 built-in administrator account must be renamed.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Accounts: Rename administrator account\" to a name other than \"Administrator\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options.\n\nIf the value for \"Accounts: Rename administrator account\" is not set to a value other than \"Administrator\", this is a finding.\n\nFor server core installations, run the following command:\n\nSecedit /Export /Areas SecurityPolicy /CFG C:\\Path\\FileName.Txt\n\nIf \"NewAdministratorName\" is not something other than \"Administrator\" in the file, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The built-in administrator account is a well-known account subject to attack. Renaming this account to an unidentified name improves the protection of this account and the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93281","SV-103369","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8626","uuid":"5094755c-e66a-4a3d-b3ab-e063d2b93b02","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205910","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205910","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205910","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205910r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205910","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000040","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 built-in guest account must be renamed.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Accounts: Rename guest account\" to a name other than \"Guest\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options.\n\nIf the value for \"Accounts: Rename guest account\" is not set to a value other than \"Guest\", this is a finding.\n\nFor server core installations, run the following command:\n\nSecedit /Export /Areas SecurityPolicy /CFG C:\\Path\\FileName.Txt\n\nIf \"NewGuestName\" is not something other than \"Guest\" in the file, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The built-in guest account is a well-known user account on all Windows systems and, as initially installed, does not require a password. This can allow access to system resources by unauthorized users. Renaming this account to an unidentified name improves the protection of this account and the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103371","V-93283","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7909","uuid":"c0180144-00e9-4c42-9743-f6e395b22025","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0E7CAA73F2749A59B64DC0C5FC37C5E51A9E2109\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 built-in guest account must be renamed.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205911","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205911","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205911","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205911r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205911","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000100","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 maximum age for machine account passwords must be configured to 30 days or less.","fix_text":"This is the default configuration for this setting (30 days).\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Maximum machine account password age\" to \"30\" or less (excluding \"0\", which is unacceptable).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This is the default configuration for this setting (30 days).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: MaximumPasswordAge\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x0000001e (30) (or less, but not 0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Computer account passwords are changed automatically on a regular basis. This setting controls the maximum password age that a machine account may have. This must be set to no more than 30 days, ensuring the machine changes its password monthly.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103373","V-93285","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3133","uuid":"66a30e6b-f00e-449a-b649-2705b67c79f6","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205912","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205912","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205912","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205912r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205912","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000150","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Smart Card removal option must be configured to Force Logoff or Lock Workstation.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Interactive logon: Smart card removal behavior\" to \"Lock Workstation\" or \"Force Logoff\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Winlogon\\\n \nValue Name: scremoveoption\n\nValue Type: REG_SZ\nValue: 1 (Lock Workstation) or 2 (Force Logoff)\n\nIf configuring this on servers causes issues, such as terminating users' remote sessions, and the organization has a policy in place that any other sessions on the servers, such as administrative console logons, are manually locked or logged off when unattended or not in use, this would be acceptable. This must be documented with the ISSO.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unattended systems are susceptible to unauthorized use and must be locked. Configuring a system to lock when a smart card is removed will ensure the system is inaccessible when unattended.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93287","SV-103375","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7226","uuid":"90ff7600-c88d-4745-9f53-09b8138d7323","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9BFAA936E974CE2BB38AF7691FA001BE12554E05\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Smart Card removal option must be configured to Force Logoff or Lock Workstation.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205913","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205913","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205913","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205913r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205913","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000210","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must not allow anonymous SID/Name translation.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network access: Allow anonymous SID/Name translation\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options.\n\nIf the value for \"Network access: Allow anonymous SID/Name translation\" is not set to \"Disabled\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing anonymous SID/Name translation can provide sensitive information for accessing a system. Only authorized users must be able to perform such translations.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103377","V-93289","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3922","uuid":"d3c94add-e81a-437d-b026-3d9ee5c24b2b","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205914","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205914","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205914","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205914r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205914","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must not allow anonymous enumeration of Security Account Manager (SAM) accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network access: Do not allow anonymous enumeration of SAM accounts\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\\n\nValue Name: RestrictAnonymousSAM\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Anonymous enumeration of SAM accounts allows anonymous logon users (null session connections) to list all accounts names, thus providing a list of potential points to attack the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93291","SV-103379","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4342","uuid":"d26447ed-f14e-449a-af52-25fbb32b3520","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CBDB8A61F26557E5695364E40DFAF6426963DDAC\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must not allow anonymous enumeration of Security Account Manager (SAM) accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205915","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205915","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205915","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205915r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205915","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000240","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to prevent anonymous users from having the same permissions as the Everyone group.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network access: Let Everyone permissions apply to anonymous users\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\\n\nValue Name: EveryoneIncludesAnonymous\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Access by anonymous users must be restricted. If this setting is enabled, anonymous users have the same rights and permissions as the built-in Everyone group. Anonymous users must not have these permissions or rights.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93293","SV-103381","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5498","uuid":"a26bc841-be9a-4166-b10a-77ed79978bc5","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 63C3A8DD93585AF18333ED0E252AE160E7CA51D7\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to prevent anonymous users from having the same permissions as the Everyone group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205916","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205916","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205916","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205916r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205916","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000260","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 services using Local System that use Negotiate when reverting to NTLM authentication must use the computer identity instead of authenticating anonymously.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: Allow Local System to use computer identity for NTLM\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\LSA\\\n\nValue Name: UseMachineId\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Services using Local System that use Negotiate when reverting to NTLM authentication may gain unauthorized access if allowed to authenticate anonymously versus using the computer identity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103383","V-93295","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2922","uuid":"6548525c-6706-4985-bbc7-e0729be15249","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 69F4D7D63FE40E55D1F4C3BBF5951EE84EC0FD63\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 services using Local System that use Negotiate when reverting to NTLM authentication must use the computer identity instead of authenticating anonymously.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205917","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205917","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205917","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205917r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205917","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000270","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must prevent NTLM from falling back to a Null session.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: Allow LocalSystem NULL session fallback\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\LSA\\MSV1_0\\\n\nValue Name: allownullsessionfallback\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"NTLM sessions that are allowed to fall back to Null (unauthenticated) sessions may gain unauthorized access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93297","SV-103385","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7635","uuid":"5bf3694c-b743-40f8-83f0-c12a1ce5e0d9","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CD8ACC1749482EA5B00B337B09DC51BF70D0310E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must prevent NTLM from falling back to a Null session.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205918","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205918","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205918","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205918r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205918","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000280","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must prevent PKU2U authentication using online identities.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: Allow PKU2U authentication requests to this computer to use online identities\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\LSA\\pku2u\\\n\nValue Name: AllowOnlineID\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"PKU2U is a peer-to-peer authentication protocol. This setting prevents online identities from authenticating to domain-joined systems. Authentication will be centrally managed with Windows user accounts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103387","V-93299","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6691","uuid":"42fb872b-51bb-4950-a447-ad9d30e06ad8","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 93C41BF3E617A3D158445708D39E92CAD4BE1166\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must prevent PKU2U authentication using online identities.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205919","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205919","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205919","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205919r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205919","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000310","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 LAN Manager authentication level must be configured to send NTLMv2 response only and to refuse LM and NTLM.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: LAN Manager authentication level\" to \"Send NTLMv2 response only. Refuse LM & NTLM\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\\n\nValue Name: LmCompatibilityLevel\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000005 (5)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The Kerberos v5 authentication protocol is the default for authentication of users who are logging on to domain accounts. NTLM, which is less secure, is retained in later Windows versions for compatibility with clients and servers that are running earlier versions of Windows or applications that still use it. It is also used to authenticate logons to standalone or nondomain-joined computers that are running later versions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103389","V-93301","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7825","uuid":"eb812fb5-a27e-4ab9-ac14-267ed979e15a","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F74D8EAC7F33E1C8E206B2CAF86B8A2ECC362F10\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 LAN Manager authentication level must be configured to send NTLMv2 response only and to refuse LM and NTLM.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205920","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205920","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205920","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205920r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205920","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000320","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to at least negotiate signing for LDAP client signing.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: LDAP client signing requirements\" to \"Negotiate signing\" at a minimum.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\LDAP\\\n\nValue Name: LDAPClientIntegrity\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This setting controls the signing requirements for LDAP clients. This must be set to \"Negotiate signing\" or \"Require signing\", depending on the environment and type of LDAP server in use.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103391","V-93303","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7133","uuid":"223a36e1-9459-4d57-a443-9095109a1f85","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3D7EADC16499A249737B8BD34B3E9FE1CA748AF1\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to at least negotiate signing for LDAP client signing.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205921","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205921","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205921","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205921r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205921","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000330","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 session security for NTLM SSP-based clients must be configured to require NTLMv2 session security and 128-bit encryption.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: Minimum session security for NTLM SSP based (including secure RPC) clients\" to \"Require NTLMv2 session security\" and \"Require 128-bit encryption\" (all options selected).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\MSV1_0\\\n\nValue Name: NTLMMinClientSec\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x20080000 (537395200)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Microsoft has implemented a variety of security support providers for use with Remote Procedure Call (RPC) sessions. All of the options must be enabled to ensure the maximum security level.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103393","V-93305","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3499","uuid":"7b3a043e-6281-4e67-a1da-acaf664c75be","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 294AFE5C069698DB0DF01F7EAC1CDA20EFF95596\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 session security for NTLM SSP-based clients must be configured to require NTLMv2 session security and 128-bit encryption.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205922","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205922","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205922","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205922r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205922","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000340","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 session security for NTLM SSP-based servers must be configured to require NTLMv2 session security and 128-bit encryption.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Network security: Minimum session security for NTLM SSP based (including secure RPC) servers\" to \"Require NTLMv2 session security\" and \"Require 128-bit encryption\" (all options selected).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Lsa\\MSV1_0\\\n\nValue Name: NTLMMinServerSec\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x20080000 (537395200)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Microsoft has implemented a variety of security support providers for use with Remote Procedure Call (RPC) sessions. All of the options must be enabled to ensure the maximum security level.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103395","V-93307","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4015","uuid":"92758d89-d8a6-4f14-991f-98729fa455f4","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 56F6D9681CD45159454B17A8CCBB1CC93B3A1A8E\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 session security for NTLM SSP-based servers must be configured to require NTLMv2 session security and 128-bit encryption.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205923","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205923","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205923","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205923r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205923","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000370","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 default permissions of global system objects must be strengthened.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"System objects: Strengthen default permissions of internal system objects (e.g., Symbolic Links)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Session Manager\\\n\nValue Name: ProtectionMode\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Windows systems maintain a global list of shared system resources such as DOS device names, mutexes, and semaphores. Each type of object is created with a default Discretionary Access Control List (DACL) that specifies who can access the objects with what permissions. When this policy is enabled, the default DACL is stronger, allowing non-administrative users to read shared objects but not to modify shared objects they did not create.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93309","SV-103397","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3054","uuid":"b8a96a97-6421-470c-b49c-8b4c81c981c1","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 88668307FC3C2FE55815FFBF4E85419299A4B6B7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 default permissions of global system objects must be strengthened.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205924","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205924","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205924","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-205924r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-205924","rule_version":"WN19-UC-000010","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must preserve zone information when saving attachments.","fix_text":"The default behavior is for Windows to mark file attachments with their zone information.\n\nIf this needs to be corrected, configure the policy value for User Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Attachment Manager >> \"Do not preserve zone information in file attachments\" to \"Not Configured\" or \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The default behavior is for Windows to mark file attachments with their zone information.\n\nIf the registry Value Name below does not exist, this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"2\", this is not a finding.\n\nIf it exists and is configured with a value of \"1\", this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_CURRENT_USER\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\Attachments\\\n\nValue Name: SaveZoneInformation\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000002 (2) (or if the Value Name does not exist)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Attachments from outside sources may contain malicious code. Preserving zone of origin (Internet, intranet, local, restricted) information on file attachments allows Windows to determine risk.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103399","V-93311","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1595","uuid":"a29911ce-9055-40f3-9b56-9a9b8e9d6c55","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205925","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205925","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205925","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","rule_id_src":"SV-205925r991591_rule","rule_id":"SV-205925","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000450","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must disable automatically signing in the last interactive user after a system-initiated restart.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Logon Options >> \"Sign-in last interactive user automatically after a system-initiated restart\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the registry value below. If it does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: DisableAutomaticRestartSignOn\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Windows can be configured to automatically sign the user back in after a Windows Update restart. Some protections are in place to help ensure this is done in a secure fashion; however, disabling this will prevent the caching of credentials for this purpose and also ensure the user is aware of the restart.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103357","V-93269","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3357","uuid":"92bd22f3-f21e-41b5-8923-d23f38f51466","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6D0BE68DE2DED00940E9F22CEDA24B5FC3D7EA04\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must disable automatically signing in the last interactive user after a system-initiated restart.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-214936","group_tree":[{"id":"V-214936","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-214936","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-214936r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-214936","rule_version":"WN19-00-000280","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must have a host-based firewall installed and enabled.","fix_text":"Install and enable a host-based firewall on the system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if a host-based firewall is installed and enabled on the system.\n\nIf a host-based firewall is not installed and enabled on the system, this is a finding.\n\nThe configuration requirements will be determined by the applicable firewall STIG.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack, allowing or blocking inbound and outbound connections based on a set of rules.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93571","SV-103657","CCI-000366","CCI-002080"],"reference_identifier":"3593","uuid":"86842a90-f204-4a24-9f1d-ebec5581547a","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CA6FF8CD36D002D078A6F7F49B3FE27DC9F469A6\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must have a host-based firewall installed and enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257503","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257503","title":"SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257503","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019","rule_id_src":"SV-257503r958420_rule","rule_id":"SV-257503","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000530","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must have PowerShell Transcription enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows PowerShell >> \"Turn on PowerShell Transcription\" to \"Enabled\".\n\nSpecify the Transcript output directory to point to a Central Log Server or another secure location to prevent user access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\PowerShell\\Transcription\\\n\nValue Name: EnableTranscripting\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 1","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nEnabling PowerShell Transcription will record detailed information from the processing of PowerShell commands and scripts. This can provide additional detail when malware has run on a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000134"],"reference_identifier":"8543","uuid":"7c1e8df8-b865-4194-8b6d-2edb55b9992e","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9DB1012993667C1B31B98D9E6DE96E582C973C90\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must have PowerShell Transcription enabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271428","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271428","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271428","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-271428r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-271428","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000391","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured for certificate-based authentication for domain controllers.","fix_text":"Configure the registry value.\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Kdc\n \nValue Name: StrongCertificateBindingEnforcement\n \nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1) or 0x00000002 (2)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. This is not applicable for member servers.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Kdc\n \nValue Name: StrongCertificateBindingEnforcement\n \nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1) or 0x00000002 (2)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Active Directory domain services elevation of privilege vulnerability could allow a user rights to the system, such as administrative and other high-level capabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"3941","uuid":"2286a99c-be99-420f-8b23-d7857c352b04","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1E007FA6845ABE080E5A7DE19F115D0B86C2D592\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured for certificate-based authentication for domain controllers.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271429","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271429","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271429","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-271429r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-271429","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000401","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured for named-based strong mappings for certificates.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Template >> System >> KDC >> Allow name-based strong mappings for certificates to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. This is not applicable for member servers.\n\nVerify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\nOr\nUsing the registry, check HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\KDC\\Parameters, Key: UseStrongNameMatches.                      \nOr\nUsing GPRESULT, check the applicable GPO for \"Allow name-based strong mappings for certificates\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Administrative Template >> System >> KDC >> Allow name-based strong mappings for certificates.\n\nIf \"Allow name-based strong mappings for certificates\" is not \"Enabled\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Weak mappings give rise to security vulnerabilities and demand hardening measures. Certificate names must be correctly mapped to the intended user account in Active Directory. A lack of strong name-based mappings allows certain weak certificate mappings, such as Issuer/Subject AltSecID and User Principal Names (UPN) mappings, to be treated as strong mappings.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"7632","uuid":"98547748-6248-45f5-a4ce-c60b8be6978c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DC0D34DA1E8467AD0B679AD5B2F94D654EDF6957\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured for named-based strong mappings for certificates.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-278934","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278934","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278934","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-278934r1135330_rule","rule_id":"SV-278934","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000581","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit file system failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit File System\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit File System auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> Audit File System.\n\nIf \"Audit File System\" is not set to \"Failure\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"1726","uuid":"0ba0fa82-6a3c-47be-8e24-4d08fa7e801f","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CC48C3CDF252335349C2F8317C992464766BC88E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit file system failures.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-278935","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278935","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278935","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-278935r1135333_rule","rule_id":"SV-278935","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000582","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit file system successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit File System\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit File System auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> Audit File System. \n\nIf \"Audit File System\" is not set to \"Success\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"6362","uuid":"f8c7220e-fb6e-4a3a-92e1-89596cae073c","stig_uuid":"2ff319bf-fec1-43f0-bab0-996ab3e3ce49","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F281D872423DD17F71CAA761D249EE953C4E0E2E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit file system successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-278936","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278936","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278936","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-278936r1135336_rule","rule_id":"SV-278936","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000583","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit handle manipulation failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Handle Manipulation\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit Handle Manipulation auditing has been enabled: \